# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: doctorate
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:doctorate/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] The first volume is dedicated to the emergence of the university in the Middle Ages and its development until around 1500.
[src:doctorate/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] Volume II describes and analyzes the university from the Reformation until the French Revolution (1500–1800), volume III the rise of the modern university until World War II (1800–1945) and the last volume the post-war period up to the present time.
[src:doctorate/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] The structure of the book follows a standardized systematic pattern throughout all volumes: the first part ("themes and patterns") introduces the reader to the university as an institution of its time.
[src:doctorate/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] The second part deals with the institutional "structures" of the university, the third with the "students", their education, activities and careers, and the fourth with individual fields of "learning" taught in the university.
[src:doctorate/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] Each section is divided into several chapters which were composed by specialists in the various subjects.
[src:doctorate/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] The main approach is holistic – the book aims less at covering the history of individual universities, but rather the character and historical trajectory of the institution as a whole.
[src:doctorate/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] As of 2011, the series has been published in full in English and German, while the first volumes have appeared in Spanish and Portuguese and translations into Russian and Chinese are in preparation.
[src:doctorate/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] In the English-language discourse, the book has been welcomed as an overhaul of Hastings Rashdall's long-time standard work *The Universities in Europe in the Middle Ages* and its 1936 revision by the medievalists F.
[src:doctorate/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] The book has received high praise from several reviewers.
[src:doctorate/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] Edward Grant regards the first part as "the best single volume on the history of medieval universities", noting its comprehensiveness, readability and authority produced by competent editorship and "outstanding contributors".
[src:doctorate/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] Susan Rosa believes that this volume "sets a standard for competency in historical research", favourably mentioning the collaborative effort which produced little overlap between the various topics.
[src:doctorate/a-history-of-the-university-in-europe] Matthew Kempshall calls the book "a product of an array of distinguished European scholars", but feels that it might have gone too far in idealizing the university as a supranational institution transcending state particularisms.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Founded in 1872 as **University College Wales, Aberystwyth**, it became a founder member of the University of Wales in 1894, and changed its name to the **University College of Wales, Aberystwyth**.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In the mid-1990s, the university again changed its name to become the **University of Wales, Aberystwyth**.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] On 1 September 2007, the University of Wales ceased to be a federal university and Aberystwyth University became independent again.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The annual income of the institution for 2024–2025 was £124.8 million of which £19.2 million was from research grants and contracts, with an expenditure of £130.3 million.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In the middle of the 19th century, eminent Welsh people were advocating the establishment of a university in the principality of Wales.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] One of these, Thomas Nicholas, whose book, *Middle and High Class Schools, and University Education for Wales* (1863), is said to have "exerted great influence on educated Welshmen".
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Funded through public and private subscriptions, and with five regional committees (London, Manchester, Liverpool, North and South Wales) guaranteeing funds for the first three years' running costs, the university opened in October 1872 with 26 students.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Thomas Charles Edwards was the principal.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In October 1875, chapels in Wales raised the next tranche of funds from over 70,000 contributors.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Until 1893, when the college joined the University of Wales as a founder member, students applying to Aberystwyth sat the University of London's entrance exams.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In 1885, a fire damaged what is now known as the Old College, Aberystwyth, and in 1897 the first 14 acres of what became the main Penglais campus were purchased.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Incorporated by royal charter in 1893, the university installed Albert Edward, Prince of Wales, as chancellor in 1896, the same year it awarded an honorary degree to the former British prime minister, William Gladstone.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The university's coat of arms dates from the 1880s.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The shield features two red dragons to symbolise Wales, and an open book to symbolise learning.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The crest, an eagle or phoenix above a flaming tower, may signify the college's rebirth after the 1885 fire.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The motto is *Nid Byd, Byd Heb Wybodaeth* ('a world without knowledge is no world at all').
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In the early 1900s, the university added courses that included law, applied mathematics, pure mathematics and botany.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The Department for International Politics, which Aberystwyth says is the oldest such department in the world, was founded in 1919.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] By 1977, the university's staff included eight Fellows of the Royal Society, such as Gwendolen Rees, the first Welsh woman to be elected an FRS.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Sports and Exercise Science was established in 2000.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Joint honours psychology degrees were introduced in September 2007, and single honours psychology in 2009.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The chancellor of the university is Dame Nicola Davies, who took up the position in January 2025.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The visitor of the university is an appointment made by the privy council, under the royal charter of the university.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Since July 2014, the holder of this office is Sir Roderick Evans.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In 2011, the university appointed a new vice chancellor under whom the academic departments were restructured as larger subject-themed institutes.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In 2022, the university celebrated its 150th anniversary, being established in 1872 (known at the time as The University College of Wales).
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The Institute of Biological, Environmental and Rural Sciences (IBERS) is a research and teaching centre which brings together staff from the Institutes of Rural Sciences and Biological Sciences and the Institute of Grassland and Environmental Research (IGER).
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Around 360 research, teaching and support staff conduct basic, strategic and applied research in biology.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The institute is located in two areas; one at the main teaching Penglais campus and another rural research hub at the Gogerddan campus.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In 1998, the Department of Economics (founded in 1912), the Department of Accounting and Finance (founded in 1979) and the Centre for Business Studies merged to create the School of Management and Business.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In 2013, the School joined the Department of Information Studies and the Department of Law and Criminology at a new campus at Llanbadarn Fawr.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The school was shortlisted for "Business School of the Year" in the *Times Higher Education* Awards (2014).
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In 2016, the institute, minus the Department of Information Studies, was renamed the Institute of Business and Law, the remaining departments being renamed Aberystwyth Business School and Aberystwyth Law School.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Computer Science (founded in 1970), conducts research in automated reasoning, computational biology, vision graphics and visualisation and intelligent robotics.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] AberMUD, the first popular internet-based MUD, was written in the department by then-student Alan Cox.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Jan Pinkava, another graduate, won an Oscar for his short animated film *Geri's Game*.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Geography and Earth Sciences (IGES) was formed, in 1989, from the former Departments of Geography (established in 1918) and Geology.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Bowen map library, containing 80,000 maps and 500 atlases.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The College of Librarianship Wales (CLW) was established at Llanbadarn Fawr in 1964, in response to a recommendation for the training of bilingual librarians that was made in the Bourdillon Report on *Standards of public library service in England* (HMSO, 1962).
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The college grew rapidly, developing close links to the Welsh speaking and professional communities, acquiring an international reputation and pioneering flexible and distance learning courses.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] It claimed to be Europe's largest institution for training librarians.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The independent college merged with the university in August 1989 and the department moved to the Penglais campus a quarter of a century later.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Following the merger, the new department took over responsibility for existing offerings in archives administration and modern records management.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The Department of International Politics is the oldest of its kind in the world.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] It was founded, shortly after the First World War in 1919, with the stated purpose of furthering political understanding of the world in the hope of avoiding such conflicts in the future.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] This goal led to the creation of the Woodrow Wilson Chair of International Politics, with Wilson having played a significant role in its creation.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The department has over 700 students from 40 countries studying at undergraduate, masters and PhD levels.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] It achieved a 95% score for student satisfaction in the 2016 National Student Survey, placing it as the highest-ranking politics department in Wales and within the UK's top ten.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The department has hosted notable academic staff in the field including E.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Carr, Leopold Kohr, Andrew Linklater, Ken Booth, Steve Smith, Michael Cox, Michael MccGwire, Jenny Edkins and Colin J.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Law and Criminology (founded in 1901) is housed in the Hugh Owen Building on the Penglais campus, and includes the *Centre for Welsh Legal Affairs*, a specialist research centre.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] All academic staff are engaged in research, and the *International Journal of Biosciences and the Law* and the *Cambrian Law Review* are edited in the department.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In 2013, the department joined the Department of Information Studies and the School of Management and Business at a new campus at Llanbadarn Fawr, as part of a newly created Institute of Management, Law and Information Studies.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In September 2018, the department moved back to the Hugh Owen Building, based in the Penglais campus, and its name changed from Aberystwyth Law School to the Department of Law and Criminology.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth has taught modern languages since 1874.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] French, German, Italian and Spanish courses are taught at both beginners' and advanced levels, in a research-active academic environment.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] One of its research projects is the *Anglo-Norman Dictionary*, based in Aberystwyth since 2001 and available online since 2005.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Physics was first taught at Aberystwyth as part of Natural Philosophy, Astronomy and Mathematics under N.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Grimley, soon after the foundation of the University College.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] It became a department in 1877, under the leadership of F.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The department was located in the south wing of what is now the Old College, but later moved to the Physics Building on the Penglais Campus.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The first chair in Physics was offered to D.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Before the First World War, much of the early research in the department was undertaken in Germany.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Early research in the 1900s was concerned with electrical conductivity and quantum theory, later moving into thermal conductivity and acoustics.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In 1931, the department hosted the Faraday Centenary Exhibition.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Williams was appointed to the Chair of Physics in 1938 where he continued his research into sub-atomic particles using a cloud chamber.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Following the Second World War, research was concerned with mechanical and nuclear physics, later moving into the fields of air density, experimental rocket launching equipment and radar.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In 2007, Aberystwyth established psychology as a "Centre for Applied Psychology" within the Department of International Politics.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] By 2011, psychology had moved into its current premises in Penbryn 5 on the Penglais Campus.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The department has over 550 undergraduate students, with degrees accredited by the British Psychological Society and is home to an MSc in Behaviour Change.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The main campus of the university is situated on Penglais Hill, overlooking the town of Aberystwyth and Cardigan Bay, and comprises most of the university buildings, Arts Centre, Students' Union, and many of the student residences.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Just below Penglais Campus is the National Library of Wales, one of Britain's five legal deposit libraries.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The landscaping of the Penglais Campus is historically significant and is listed at Grade II* on the Cadw/ICOMOS Register of Parks and Gardens of Special Historic Interest in Wales.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The Llanbadarn Centre is located approximately one mile to the east of the Penglais Campus, near Llanbadarn Fawr, overlooking the town and Cardigan Bay to the west, with the backdrop of the Cambrian Mountains to the east.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Llanbadarn Centre hosted Aberystwyth Law School and Aberystwyth Business School, which together formed the Institute of Business and Law.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Information Studies is also based there.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Additionally, the Llanbadarn Campus is the site of the Aberystwyth branch of Coleg Ceredigion (a further education college, and not part of the university).
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] At Gogerddan, on the outskirts of town is located the university's major centre for research in land based sciences and the main centre for the Institute of Biological, Environmental and Rural Science.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The School of Art is located between the Penglais Campus and the centre of Aberystwyth, in what was originally the Edward Davies Memorial Chemistry Laboratories.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] A listed building, the Edward Davies Building is one of the finest examples of architecture in Aberystwyth.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The site of the original university is the Old College, currently the subject of the "New Life for Old College" project which aims to transform it into an integrated centre of heritage, culture, learning and knowledge exchange.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The university opened an international campus in Mauritius in 2015 operating as *Aberystwyth University (Mauritian Branch Campus)* and registered with the Tertiary Education Commission of Mauritius, but closed it to new enrolments two years later due to low enrolment numbers.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Less than 200 students enrolled with the Mauritius campus, which had the capacity for 2,000 students, before its 2018 closure and the university lost more than a million pounds as a result of the venture.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Most of the student residences are on campus, with the rest in walking distance of the campus and Aberystwyth town centre.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Accommodation ranges from "traditional" catered residences to en-suite self-catered accommodation, and from budget rooms to more luxurious studio apartments.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] All have wired access to the university's computer network and a support network of residential tutors.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Disabled access rooms are available within the existing student village.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth University is placed in the UK's top 40 universities in the main national rankings.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] It is ranked 38th for 132 UK university rankings in *The Times/Sunday Times Good University Guide* for 2023, and the first university to be given the prestigious award "University of the year for teaching quality" for two consecutive years, in 2018 and 2019.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The *Times Higher Education World University Rankings* placed it in the 301—350 group for 800 university rankings, compared with 351—400 the previous year, and the *QS World University Rankings* placed it at the 432nd position for 2019, compared with 481—490 of the previous year.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In 2015, UK employers from "predominantly business, IT and engineering sectors" listed Aberystwyth equal 49th in their 62-place employability rankings for UK graduates, according to a *Times Higher Education* report.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth University was rated in the top ten of UK higher education institutions for overall student satisfaction in the 2016 National Student Survey (NSS).
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth University was shortlisted in four categories in the *Times Higher Education* Leadership and Management Awards (THELMAs) (2015).
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth University has been awarded the Silver Award under the Corporate Health Standard (CHS), the quality mark for workplace health promotion run by Welsh Government.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The university has been awarded an Athena SWAN Charter Award, recognising commitment to advancing women's careers in science, technology, engineering, maths and medicine (STEMM) in higher education and research.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In 2007, the university came under criticism for its record on sustainability, ranking 97th out of 106 UK higher education institutions in that year's Green League table.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In 2012 the university was listed in the table's "Failed, no award" section, ranking equal 132nd out of 145.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In 2013 it ranked equal 135th out of 143, and was listed again as "Failed, no award".
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Following the university's initiatives to address sustainability, it received an EcoCampus Silver Phase award in October 2014.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In October 2015, the university's Penglais Campus became the first university campus in Wales to achieve the Green Flag Award.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The Green Flag Award is a UK-wide partnership, delivered in Wales by Keep Wales Tidy with support from Natural Resources Wales, and is the mark of a high quality park or green space.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In 2013, the University and College Union alleged bullying behaviour by Aberystwyth University managers, and said staff were fearful for their jobs.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The singer Peter Karrie resigned his honorary fellowship in protest, he said, at the apparent determination to "ruin one of the finest arts centres in the country", and because he was "unable to support any regime that can treat their staff in such a cruel and appalling manner".
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] In Autumn 2024, students protested the reduction of opening hours at Hugh Owen Library, a cost-cutting measure.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] Students argued that the university had continued to promote their 24/7 Library until recent open days, and that they were going back on promises which had attracted many students to the University.
[src:doctorate/aberystwyth-university] The University initially met with students to discuss options to restore the library's original opening hours, but later rejected further requests for meetings, and refused to negotiate any further.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] An **academic certificate** or **tech certificate** is a document that certifies that a person has received specific education or has passed a test or series of tests.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] In many countries, a certificate is a qualification attained in secondary education.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] For instance, students in Ireland sit the Junior Certificate and follow it with the Leaving Certificate.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] Similarly, other countries have awards, for instance, in Australia the Higher School Certificate (HSC) in New South Wales, the Victorian Certificate of Education (VCE) in Victoria, etc., is the examination taken on completion of secondary education.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] In parts of the United Kingdom the General Certificate of Secondary Education (GCSE) is the normal examination taken at age 16 and the General Certificate of Education (GCE) Advanced Subsidiary Level (AS-level) and Advanced Level (A-levels) are taken at 17 and 18.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] In many other countries, certificates are qualifications in higher education.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] For example, the National Certificate in Ireland, which was replaced in 2006 by the "Higher Certificate".
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] These have the titles Certificate (at an undergraduate level), Graduate Certificate (at an undergraduate level, but requiring the completion of a prior undergraduate degree for admission), and Postgraduate Certificate (at a postgraduate level).
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] In Hong Kong, students take the exams to receive Hong Kong Diploma of Secondary Education.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] Certificate is below the standard of the associate degree, diploma, higher diploma and advanced diploma, which are below the bachelor's degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] Postgraduate certificates are taken after the bachelor's degree and are sometimes more vocationally oriented than master's degrees.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] In Australia, a certificate is a qualification offered by a university or other higher education provider which is shorter than a degree or diploma.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] Certificates are generally provided by TAFE colleges or non-academic registered training organizations (often workplaces).
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] There are four ranks of certificate in Australia, indicated by Roman numerals, e.g., Cert.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] The time spent varies, but in general a Certificate I will be granted after a course of only a few weeks, while a Cert.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] IV and may rightly be considered equivalent to a hypothetical Certificate V.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] In the United Kingdom, a Certificate of Higher Education (CertHE) requires successful completion of 120 credits at level four of the Framework for Higher Education Qualifications (level 7 of the Scottish Credit and Qualifications Framework).
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] This is equivalent to one year of full-time university education at first-year level.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] Each credit is equivalent to a nominal ten hours of study, and as such the CertHE is 1,200 hours of study.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] This compares with 360 credits (spanning levels 4, 5 and 6/480 credits spanning levels 7 to 10 in Scotland) for an honours bachelor's degree, and 240 credits (spanning level 4 and 5/7 and 8 in Scotland) for a Diploma of Higher Education.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] A certificate can also be a vocational qualification of between 13 and 36 credits at any of the levels of the Regulated Qualifications Framework, the level being specified in the qualification title.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] In the United States, a certificate may be offered by an institute of higher education.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] These certificates usually signify that a student has reached a standard of knowledge about a certain vocational or professional subject.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] Certificate programs can be completed more quickly than associate degrees and often do not have general education requirements.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] Undergraduate certificates represent completion of a specific program offered in coordination with a bachelor's degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] Graduate certificates represent completion of studies beyond the bachelor's degree, yet short of a master's degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] It also may be awarded as a necessary certification to validate that a student is considered competent in a certain specific networking skill area in information technology.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] It is becoming more common for higher education institutions to award certificates to continuing education students.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] These certificates vary, usually involve rigorous courses, and can be affiliated with many associations.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] University certificates are also becoming more common ways for people to engage in areas of interest while working full-time.
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] They can be completed with a minimum grade in a series of university courses, and are sometimes taken as a way to further one's professional career (either by requirement or choice).
[src:doctorate/academic-certificate] They are gaining credence and ground in both the academic world and the working world.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] An **academic degree** is a qualification awarded to a student upon successful completion of a course of study in higher education.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Academic degrees are commonly structured in levels, most often categorized as undergraduate and postgraduate degrees.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] The most common undergraduate qualification is the bachelor's degree, although some educational systems also offer lower-level degrees such as the associate degree or the foundation degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Postgraduate degrees include the engineer's degree, the master's degree, and the doctorate.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] In the UK and countries whose educational systems are based on the British system, honours degrees are divided into classes: first, second (broken into upper second, or 2.1, and lower second, or 2.2) and third class.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] The doctorate (Latin: *doceo*, "I teach") first appeared in medieval Europe as a license to teach (Latin: *licentia docendi*) at a medieval university.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Its roots can be traced to the early church when the term "doctor" referred to the Apostles, Church Fathers and other Christian authorities who taught and interpreted the Bible.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] The right to grant a *licentia docendi* was originally reserved by the church which required the applicant to pass a test, take an oath of allegiance, and pay a fee.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] The Third Council of the Lateran of 1179 guaranteed the access – now largely free of charge – of all able applicants, who were, however, still tested for aptitude by the ecclesiastic scholastic.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] This right remained a point of contention between the church authorities and the slowly emancipating universities, but was granted by the Pope to the University of Paris in 1231 where it became a universal license to teach (*licentia ubique docendi*).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] While the *licentia* continued to hold a higher prestige than the bachelor's degree (*Baccalaureus*), it was ultimately reduced to an intermediate step to the Magister and doctorate, both of which now became the exclusive qualification for teaching.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] In universities, doctoral training was a form of apprenticeship to a guild.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] The traditional term of study before new teachers were admitted to the guild of "Master of Arts" was seven years.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] This was the same as the term of apprenticeship for other occupations.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Originally the terms "master" and "doctor" were synonymous, but over time the doctorate came to be regarded as a higher qualification than the master's degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Today the terms "master" (from the Latin *magister*, lit.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] 'teacher'), "Doctor", and "Professor" signify different levels of academic achievement, but in the Medieval university, they were equivalent terms.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] The use of them in the degree name was a matter of custom at a university.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Most universities conferred the Master of Arts, although the highest degree was often termed Master of Theology/Divinity or Doctor of Theology/Divinity, depending on the place.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] The earliest doctoral degrees (theology – *Divinitatis* Doctor (D.D.), law – *Legum* Doctor (LL.D., later D.C.L.) and medicine – *Medicinæ* Doctor (M.D., D.M.)) reflected the historical separation of all higher university study into these three fields.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Over time, the D.D. has gradually become less common outside theology and is now mostly used for honorary degrees, with the title "Doctor of Theology" being used more often for earned degrees.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Studies outside theology, law, and medicine were then called "philosophy", due to the Renaissance conviction that real knowledge could be derived from empirical observation.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] The degree title of Doctor of Philosophy is a much later creation and was not introduced in England before 1900.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Studies in what once was called philosophy are now classified as sciences and humanities.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] George Makdisi theorizes that the *ijazah* issued in medieval Islamic madrasas in the 9th century was the origin of the doctorate that later appeared in medieval European universities.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Alfred Guillaume, Syed Farid al-Attas and Devin J.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Stewart agree that there is a resemblance between the *ijazah* and the university degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] However, Toby Huff and others reject Makdisi's theory.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Stewart finds that the *ijazat al-ifta*, license to teach Islamic law and issue legal opinions, is most similar to the medieval European university degree in that it permits entry into certain professions.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] A key difference was that the granting authority of the *ijaza* was an individual professor whereas the university degree was granted by a corporate entity.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] The University of Bologna in Italy, regarded as the oldest university in Europe, was the first institution to confer the degree of Doctor in Civil Law in the late 12th century; it also conferred similar degrees in other subjects, including medicine.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] The University of Paris used the term "master" for its graduates, a practice adopted by the English universities of Oxford and Cambridge, as well as the ancient Scottish universities of St Andrews, Glasgow, Aberdeen and Edinburgh.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] The term "bachelor" comes from the Latin *baccalaureus*, a term previously used to describe a squire (i.e., apprentice) to a knight.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Further study and, in particular, successful participation in, and moderation of, disputations would earn one the Master of Arts degree, from the Latin magister, "master" (typically indicating a teacher), entitling one to teach these subjects.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Masters of Arts were eligible to enter study under the "higher faculties" of Law, Medicine or Theology and earn first a bachelor's and then master's or doctor's degree in these subjects.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Thus, a degree was only a step on the way to becoming a fully qualified master – hence the English word "graduate", which is based on the Latin *gradus* ("step").
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] The naming of degrees eventually became linked to the subjects studied.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Scholars in the faculties of arts or grammar became known as "masters", but those in theology, medicine and law were known as "doctors".
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] As a study in the arts or grammar was a necessary prerequisite to study in subjects such as theology, medicine and law, the degree of doctor assumed a higher status than the master's degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] This led to the modern hierarchy in which the Doctor of Philosophy (Ph.D.), which in its present form as a degree based on research and dissertation is a development from 18th- and 19th-century German universities, is a more advanced degree than the Master of Arts (M.A.).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] The practice of using the term *doctor* for PhDs developed within German universities and spread across the academic world.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] The French terminology is tied closely to the original meanings of the terms.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] "bachelor") is conferred upon French students who have completed their secondary education and allows the student to attend university.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] When students graduate from university, they are awarded a *licence*, much as the medieval teaching guilds would have done, and they are qualified to teach in secondary schools or proceed to higher-level studies.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Spain had a similar structure: the term *"Bachiller"* was used for those who finished the secondary or high-school level education, known as *"Bachillerato"*.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] The standard Spanish university 5-year degree was *"Licenciado"*, (although there were a few 3-year associate degrees called *"diplomaturas"*, from where the *"diplomados"* could move to study a related *licenciatura*).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] In the past, degrees have been directly issued by the authority of the monarch or by a bishop, rather than any educational institution.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] In Great Britain, Lambeth degrees are still awarded by the Archbishop of Canterbury.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] The Archbishop of Canterbury's right to grant degrees is derived from the Peter's Pence Act 1533, which empowered the Archbishop to grant dispensations previously granted by the Pope.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Among educational institutions, St David's College, Lampeter, was granted limited degree awarding powers by royal charter in the nineteenth century, despite not being a university.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] The University College of North Staffordshire was also granted degree awarding powers on its foundation in 1949, despite not becoming a university (as the University of Keele) until 1962.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Following the Education Reform Act 1988, many educational institutions other than universities have been granted degree-awarding powers, including higher education colleges and colleges of the University of London, many of which are now effectively universities in their own right.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] In many countries, gaining an academic degree entitles the holder to assume distinctive academic dress particular to the awarding institution, identifying the status of the individual wearing them.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] In many countries, degrees may only be awarded by institutions authorised to do so by the national or regional government.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Frequently, governments will also regulate the use of the word *university* in the names of businesses.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] This approach is followed, for example, by Australia, the United Kingdom and Israel.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] The use of fake degrees by individuals, either obtained from a bogus institution or simply invented, is often covered by fraud laws.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Depending on the culture and the degree earned, degrees may be indicated by a pre-nominal title, post-nominal letters, a choice of either, or not indicated at all.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] In countries influenced by the UK, post-nominal letters are the norm, with only doctorates granting a title, while titles are the norm in many northern European countries.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Depending on the culture and the purpose of the listing, only the highest degree, a selection of degrees, or all degrees might be listed.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] The awarding institution may be shown and it might be specified if a degree was at honours level, particularly where the honours degree is a separate qualification from the ordinary bachelor's degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] For member institutions of the Association of Commonwealth Universities, there is a standard list of abbreviations for university names given in the Commonwealth Universities Yearbook.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] In practice, many variations are used and the Yearbook notes that the abbreviations used may not match those used by the universities concerned.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Other Latin abbreviations commonly used include 'Cantuar' for Lambeth degrees (awarded by the Archbishop of Canterbury), 'Dunelm' for Durham University, 'Ebor' for the University of York and 'Exon' for the University of Exeter.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] The Ancient universities of Scotland and the University of London have abbreviations that are the same in English and Latin.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Confusion can result from universities sharing similar names, e.g. the University of York in the UK and York University in Canada or Newcastle University in the UK and the University of Newcastle in Australia.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] In this case, the convention is to include a country abbreviation with the university's name.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] For example, 'York (Can.)' and 'York (UK)' or 'Newc (UK)' and 'Newc (Aus.) are commonly used to denote degrees conferred by these universities where the potential for confusion exists, and institution names are given in this form in the Commonwealth Universities Yearbook.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Abbreviations used for degrees vary between countries and institutions, e.g.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] MS indicates Master of Science in the US and places following American usage, but Master of Surgery in the UK and most Commonwealth countries, where the standard abbreviation for Master of Science is MSc.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Common abbreviations include BA and MA for Bachelor and Master of Arts, BS/BSc and MS/MSc for Bachelor and Master of Science, MD for Doctor of Medicine and PhD for Doctor of Philosophy.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p01] Improvements in technology, the increasing use of the Internet worldwide, and the need for people to have flexible school schedules that enable them to work while attending school have led to a proliferation of online colleges that award associate's, bachelor's, master's, and doctoral degrees.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Bangladesh and India mostly follow the colonial era British system for the classification of degrees, however, Pakistan has recently switched to the US model of a two-year associate degree and a four-year bachelor's degree program.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The arts, referring to the performing arts and literature, may confer a Bachelor of Arts (BA) and a Master of Arts (MA).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Management degrees are also classified under 'arts' but are nowadays considered a separate stream, with degrees of Bachelor of Business Administration (BBA) and Master of Business Administration (MBA).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Science refers to the basic sciences and natural science (Biology, Physics, Chemistry, etc.); the corresponding degrees are Bachelor of Science (BSc) and Master of Science (MSc).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Information Technology degrees are conferred specially in the field of computer science, and include Bachelor of Science in Information Technology (B.Sc.IT.) and Master of Science in Information Technology (M.Sc.IT.).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The engineering degree in India follows two nomenclatures, Bachelor of Engineering (B.Eng.) and Bachelor of Technology (B.Tech.).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Both represent bachelor's degree in engineering.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] In Pakistan, engineering degrees are Bachelor of Engineering (B.E.) and Bachelor of Science in Engineering (B.S./B.Sc.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Both are the same in curriculum, duration and pattern, and differ only in nomenclature.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The engineering degree in Bangladesh is a Bachelor of Science in Engineering (B.Sc.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Indonesia follows a higher education system that originated from the Dutch colonial period.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] However, over the years, Indonesia has transitioned from the Dutch degree classification system and developed its own academic distinctions by translating and adapting its degree structure.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] All degrees in Indonesia follow standardized regulations.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The duration of each program is specified by Regulation of the Minister of Education and Culture of the Republic of Indonesia Number 3 of 2020 on National Standards of Higher Education.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The regulation outlines the maximum duration and minimum credit requirements (Semester Credit Units or SKS) for each level of study without counting academic leave.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The degree structure follows a standardized pattern, where XX represents the specific field of study.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Since a semester consists of 14 or 15 weeks of coursework and 1 or 2 weeks of exams, one SKS translates to an average of 40 hours of study per semester.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Comparatively, one European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System (ECTS) credit equals 28 hours of study, meaning that one Indonesian SKS is approximately equivalent to 1.5 ECTS.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Therefore, a bachelor's degree in Indonesia (minimum 144 SKS) is roughly equivalent to 216 ECTS, which surpasses the standard European requirement of 180 ECTS for a bachelor's degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] All degrees in Indonesia grant academic titles, which are often used in formal and social settings, including on unofficial documents such as marriage invitations.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Before Indonesia adopted its modern degree classification, the country used a system copied from the Dutch colonial academic structure, which in Netherlands remained extant to 2002.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] In this system, university students typically studied for five years before graduating.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] This structure was different from the modern four-year bachelor's (S1) degree, as it allowed graduates to proceed directly to a doctorate (S3) program without first obtaining a master's (S2) degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] This system included pre-nominal academic titles that have largely been phased out but are still recognized, for those who graduated before 1992.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Some of these titles are still in limited use today.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Doktorandus (Drs.) and Doktoranda (Dra.) originated from Latin, meaning "one who is to become a doctor." These titles indicated that the degree holder only needed to complete a dissertation to obtain a doctorate.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Until the 1960s, diplomas from Bandung Institute of Technology (ITB) explicitly stated that holders were entitled to pursue a doctorate upon defending a thesis.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] After the 1970s, ITB replaced Doktorandus and Insinyur (Engineer) titles with Sarjana (Bachelor) degrees.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] However, these titles remained granted and used until 1992 in other universities or institutes.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] By aligning with Anglo education standards, Indonesia transitioned to the B.Sc. - M.Sc. - Ph.D. model, similar to the Bologna Process.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Unlike the previous system, where five-year graduates could proceed directly to a Ph.D., students must now complete an S1 (Bachelor's) and S2 (Master's) before pursuing S3 (Doctorate).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Despite this transition, many pre-1992 graduates retained the use of their original titles granted upon their graduation, making formats such as Prof.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Drs. [Name] common among senior academics and professionals.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Sri Lanka, like many other commonwealth countries, follows the British system, but with its own distinctions.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Degrees are approved by the University Grants Commission.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Tunisia's educational grading system, ranging from elementary school to Ph.D. programs, operates on a scale of 0 to 20.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The minimum score for passing is set at 10 out of 20.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] This numerical system exclusively evaluates a student's academic accomplishments, serving as the determinant for admission into advanced programs.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] For instance, a student's grades obtained for their bachelor's degree are considered when they apply for a Master's program.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Level 4 courses, which include the first year of a Bachelor's program or a Higher National Certificate (HNC), may allow students to enter directly into the second year of a Bachelor's program, provided that the course they completed is the same as the one they are applying for.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] In South Africa, grades (also known as "marks") are presented as a percentage, with anything below 50% considered a failure.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Students who receive a failing grade may have the opportunity to rewrite the exam, depending on the criteria established by their institution.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Degrees in almost any field of study can be pursued at one of the institutions in the country, with certain institutions being known for excelling in specific fields.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Major fields of study across the country include Arts, Commerce, Engineering, Law, Medicine, Science, and Theology.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The South African Qualifications Authority (SAQA) has developed a credit-based system for degrees, with different levels of National Qualifications Framework (NQF) ratings corresponding to each degree level.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] For example, an undergraduate degree in Science is rated at NQF level 6, while an additional year of study in that discipline would result in an NQF level 8 (honours degree) rating.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] In Kenya, the first undergraduate degree is pursued after students have completed four years of secondary school education and attained at least a C+ (55–59%) on the Kenya Certificate of Secondary Education (KCSE).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Students pursuing a degree in engineering, such as B.Sc.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Electrical and Electronics Engineering, are required to join programs that are accredited by the Engineers Board of Kenya and the Commission for University Education.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The B.Sc. degree in engineering typically takes five years to complete.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] A degree in medicine or surgery may take six to seven years, while a degree in education or management takes around four years.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] For students pursuing a master's degree, they must have completed an undergraduate degree and attained at least a second-class honours upper division (60–69%) or lower division plus at least two years of relevant experience.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Most master's degree programs take two years to complete.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] In an engineering master's degree program, students are typically required to publish at least one scientific paper in a peer-reviewed journal.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] To pursue a doctor of philosophy degree, students must have completed a relevant master's degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] They are required to carry out a supervised scientific study for a minimum of three years and publish at least two scientific first-author papers in peer-reviewed journals relevant to their area of study.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Currently, Kenya is implementing a Competency Based Curriculum (CBC) that follows a 2–6–3–3 education system to replace the existing 8–4–4 system which allows confirmation of undergraduate degrees upon successful completion.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] This system is gradually replacing the two-stage system previously used in some countries and is combined with other elements such as the European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System (ECTS) and the use of Diploma Supplements to make comparisons between qualifications easier.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The European Higher Education Area (EHEA) was formally established in 2010 and, as of September 2016, has 50 members.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The implementation of the various elements of the EHEA varies between countries.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Twenty-four countries have fully implemented a national qualifications framework, and a further ten have a framework but have not yet certified it against the overarching framework.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] In 38 countries, ECTS credits are used for all higher education programmes, and 31 countries have fully implemented diploma supplements.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Only 11 countries have included all the major points of the Lisbon Recognition Convention in national legislation.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Since 2008, the European Union has been developing the European Qualifications Framework (EQF).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] This is an eight-level framework designed to allow cross-referencing of the various national qualifications frameworks.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] While it is not specific to higher education, the top four levels (5–8) correspond to the short cycle, first cycle, second cycle, and third cycle of the EHEA.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The two-cycle degree system was phased out by 2010, with a few exceptions.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] However, some of the established degree naming has been preserved, allowing universities to award the "Diplom-Ingenieur" (and for a while also the "Magister") to graduates of the new-style Master programmes.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] While higher education is regulated by the three communities of Belgium, all have common and comparable systems of degrees that were adapted to the Bologna structure during the 2000s.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The primary 3-cycle structure is called BMD (Bachelor-Master-Doctorate; French: *Bachelier-Master-Doctorat* or Dutch: *Bachelor-Master-Doctoraat*).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] In the first cycle, the Bachelor's degree is issued after 180 ECTS (3 years, EQF level 6).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Other first cycle degrees include the one-year Advanced Bachelor's degree degree (French: *Bachelier de spécialisation*, lit.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] 'Specialized Bachelor'; Dutch: *Bachelor-na-bachelor*, lit.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] 'Bachelor-after-bachelor') and the Brevet (in the French-speaking Community only) for short-cycle higher education programmes.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Bachelor's degrees are followed in the second cycle (EQF level 7) by Master's degrees that last two years, completing an extra 120 ECTS credits.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The master's degree can be followed by an Advanced Master's degree (French: *Master de spécialisation*, lit.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] 'Specialized Master'; Dutch: *Master-na-master*, lit.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] 'Master-after-master') that lasts one year (60 ECTS).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The Czech Republic has implemented the Bologna process, and functionally has three degrees: Bachelor (3 years), Master (2 years after Bachelor) and Doctor (4 years after Master).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The Czech Republic also has voluntary academic titles called "small doctorates" (e.g.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] RNDr. for natural sciences, PhDr. for philosophy, JUDr. for law etc.) which are achieved after passing an additional exam.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Medical students do not get bachelor's or master's degrees, but instead attend a six-year program and obligatory exam they achieve the title MUDr.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] (equivalent to MD degree in the United States of America), or MDDr. for dentists and MVDr. for veterinary physicians.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] They can also get a "big doctorate" (Ph.D.) after another three or four years of study.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Bachelor's degrees, master's degrees and small doctorates in the form of letters (Bc., Mgr., Ing., ...) are listed before the person's name, and Doctor's degrees (Ph.D.) are listed after name (e.g.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The Czech Republic previously had more degrees that were awarded.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Before the adoption of the Bologna Process, the lowest degree that would normally be studied at universities in Denmark was equivalent to a master's degree (*kandidatgrad*).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Officially, a bachelor's degree was always obtained after 3 years' university studies.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Various medium-length (2–4 years) professional degrees have been adopted, so they now have status as professional bachelor's degrees of varying length.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] As opposed to academic bachelor's degrees, they are considered to be "applied" degrees.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] A professional bachelor's degree is 180, 210, or 240 ECTS-points.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Historically, the Finnish higher education system is derived from the German system.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The current system of higher education comprises two types of higher education institutions, the universities and the polytechnics, many of whom refer to themselves as universities of applied sciences (UAS).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] With the exception of a few fields, such as medicine and dentistry, the Finnish system of higher education degrees is in compliance with the Bologna process.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Universities award bachelor's degrees (*kandidaatti / kandidat*), Master's degrees (*maisteri / magister*) and doctoral degrees (*lisensiaatin tutkinto / licentiat examen* and *tohtorin tutkinto / doktorexamen*).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] In most fields, the system of doctoral degrees is two-tier, the degree of licentiate is an independent academic degree but completing the degree of doctor does not require completion of a licentiate degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The polytechnics (universities of applied sciences) have the right to award bachelor's and master's degrees; the degree titles are distinct from the titles used for university degrees.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] In general, students who are admitted to bachelor studies at a university have the right to continue to studies at master level.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] At polytechnics, the right to continue to master-level studies has to be applied for separately and there is also a work experience requirement.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The majority of master's degree holders have graduated from university.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The degrees awarded by the universities and polytechnics are at par by law, but the content and orientation of studies is different.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] A master's degree obtained at a polytechnic gives the same academic right to continue studies at doctoral level as a master's degree obtained at a university.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The French national education system makes a distinction between a *diplôme national* ("national degree") and *diplôme universitaire* ("university degree").
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The former, which are considered to have a higher status, are controlled by the state and issued by universities on behalf of the responsible ministry; the latter are controlled and granted by the universities themselves.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Additionally, private universities and schools may be recognised by the state with a *diplôme visé* ("recognised degree") and then, after five years of recognition, have their degrees validated by the state, the validation having to be renewed every six years.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Historically, academic degrees were orientated towards research, and the vocational education system awarded only diplomas.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Since the implementation of the Bologna Process in France, the degree-granting system is being simplified: schools continue to grant their own diplomas, but the state's recognition in degree awarding is more important than before.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] However, in France there are diplomas that are not recognised as degrees, such as specific diplomas designed by colleges (*écoles supérieures*), like the *mastère spécialisé* (accredited by the *Conférence des Grandes Écoles* but not automatically by the French Government).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Since 2002, *grande école* diplomas have been able to award a university degree, such as the Sciences Po *Bachelor*, which is a state-accredited diploma that awards a bachelor's degree (*Licence* in French).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] The recognised degrees are in three levels, following the Qualifications Framework of the European Higher Education Area.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] These are the *licence* (first level), *master* (second level) and *doctorat* (third level).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] All licence degrees take 3 years (180 ECTS credits) and all master's degrees take 2 years (120 ECTS credits).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] There are also 5-year (300 ECTS credits) engineer's degrees, which are master's degrees.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] In addition to the doctorate, which is always a research degree, the *Diplôme d'Etat de docteur en médicine* and the *Diplôme d'Etat de docteur vétérinaire* are third level qualifications and recognized as level 7 in EQF.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] Traditionally in Germany, students studied for four to six years and then graduated with either a *Magister* degree (usually in subjects like humanities, linguistics or the arts) or a *Diplom* degree (typically in fields such as natural sciences, economics, or engineering).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p02] These qualifications were usually the first and highest academic degrees students earned before a doctorate.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Both Magister and Diplom degrees from universities required a final thesis and are generally considered equivalent to a modern master’s degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] However, the Diplom awarded by a *Fachhochschule* (university of applied sciences) is usually considered comparable to a bachelor’s degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] A different type of qualification in Germany is the *Staatsexamen* (state examination).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] This is not an academic degree but a government licensing examination required for certain professions, such as doctors, teachers, lawyers, judges, and pharmacists.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Students typically study at university for three to six years before taking the first Staatsexamen, depending on their field.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] After passing the first Staatsexamen, candidates in fields like law and teaching must complete a practical training period called the *Vorbereitungsdienst* (preparatory service), which usually lasts about two years.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] They then take a second Staatsexamen, which tests their practical skills.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] In some cases, students of law or pharmacy can choose to graduate with a master’s degree instead of taking the first Staatsexamen.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Since 1999, Germany has replaced its traditional university degrees with bachelor’s and master’s degrees as part of the Bologna process.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] This reform aimed to make degrees more comparable internationally and to shorten the overall time students spend in higher education, as older programs often took five years or more to complete.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Today, students typically complete a bachelor’s degree followed by a master’s degree; the first usually taking 3 years, and the latter taking 18 months to 2 years.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Some universities resisted the change, but by the end of 2007 all institutions were required to adopt the new system.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Degree programs that lead to a Staatsexamen (state examination), such as those in law or medicine, were generally not converted to the bachelor’s/master’s system.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] In Germany, doctoral degrees are awarded with different titles depending on the subject area.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Examples include Doktor der Naturwissenschaften (Doctor of Natural Sciences), Doktor der Rechtswissenschaften (Doctor of Law), Doktor der Medizin (Doctor of Medicine), and Doktor der Philosophie (Doctor of Philosophy).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] In German-speaking countries, it is common for people to list multiple doctorates and honorary titles, and sometimes even use them in formal address.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Students who have completed a Diplom, Magister, master’s degree, or Staatsexamen can usually continue on to a doctorate.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] In some cases, particularly strong bachelor’s graduates may also be admitted directly to a doctoral program after passing an aptitude assessment set by the university.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Doctoral degrees (such as Dr. rer. nat. or Dr. phil.) are the highest academic qualifications in Germany and are typically based on independent research.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] (Doctor of Medicine): medical doctors often complete their doctoral thesis shortly after finishing their studies, and it may involve less independent research compared to doctorates in other fields.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Unlike some countries such as the United Kingdom, Germany does not have a system of “higher doctorates” (such as the Doctor of Science).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The Habilitation is an additional qualification beyond the doctorate, although it is not an academic degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] It demonstrates the ability to carry out advanced research and teach at the university level.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] To obtain a Habilitation, candidates usually write a second thesis (called a *Habilitationsschrift*) or submit a collection of significant research publications.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Once completed, the qualification is sometimes abbreviated as “habil.” after a person’s name.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Traditionally, the Habilitation was required to become a *Privatdozent* (a university lecturer qualified to teach independently) and to pursue a professorship.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Today, universities no longer require it, although it can still be an advantage in more traditional academic fields.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] In Greece access to university is possible after national exams (Panhellenic Exams).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Ireland operates under a National Framework of Qualifications (NFQ).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The school-leaving qualification attained by students is called the Leaving Certificate.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] It is considered as Level 4–5 in the framework.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] This qualification is the traditional route of entry into third-level education.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] There are also Level 5 qualifications in certain vocational subjects (e.g.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Level 5 Certificate in Restaurant Operations) awarded by the Further Education and Training Awards Council (FETAC).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Advanced Certificates at Level 6 are also awarded by FETAC.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] These are completed in institutes of technology or universities.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] In Italy access to university is possible after gaining the *Diploma di Maturità* at 19 years of age, following 5 years of study in a specific high school focused on certain subjects (e.g.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] After gaining the diploma one can enter university and enrol in any curriculum (e.g. physics, medicine, chemistry, engineering, architecture): all high school diplomas allow access to any university curriculum, although most universities have pre-admission tests.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] In addition to academic degrees, many professional qualifications are tied to the QTI at the different levels.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The first level, tied to the first cycle of the Bologna Process, covers the *laurea* (bachelor's degree) in universities and the *Diploma accademico di primo livello* in AFAM institutions.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The *laurea* is obtained after three years of study (180 ECTS credits) and confers the academic title of *dottore*; the older university qualifications at this level took two to three years, with the three-year courses conferring the title of *dottore*.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The second level, tied to the second cycle of the Bologna Process, covers the *laurea magistrale* and the *laurea specialistica* of university institutions, and the *Diploma accademico di secondo livello* of AFAM institutions.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The old *Diploma di laurea* is mapped to this level.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The *Laurea magistrale* and the *laurea specialistica* are obtained after two further years of study (120 ECTS credits) and give the academic title of *dottore magistrale*.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The old *Diploma di laurea* took four to six years but was accessed directly from school, with a possible reduction by one year for those with a related *diploma* and also granted the title of *dottore magistrale*.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The third level, tied to the third cycle of the Bologna Process, covers the *Dottorato di ricerca* from university institutions and the *Diploma accademico di formazione alla ricerca* from AFAM institutions.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The old *Dottorato di ricerca* and *Diploma di specializzazione* are tied to this level.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The *Dottorato di ricerca*, under both new and old systems, takes a minimum of three years after the *laurea magistralie/specialistica*, and gives the academic titles of *Dottore di Ricerca (Dott.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The old *Diploma di specializzazione* took two to six years and gave the academic title of *Specialista*.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The *Diploma di specializzazione*, which is offered in a few specific professions, takes two to six years and gives the title of *specialista*.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The *Diploma di perfezionamento* is a university certificate, aimed at professional training or in specific fields of study, which usually takes one year; it is not allocated a level in the framework.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] AFAM institutions may offer the *Diploma di perfezionamento o Master* and *Diploma accademico di specializzazione*.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] These are one-year and two-year qualifications, respectively, and may be offered at the second cycle or third cycle level, distinguished by adding *(I)* or *(II)* after the qualification name.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Higher schools for language mediators offer the *Diploma di mediatore linguistico*, a first-cycle degree that takes three years (180 ECTS credits), and which gives access to the *laurea specialistica*.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Specialisation institutes/schools in psychotherapy offer the *Diploma di specializzazione in psicoterapia*, a third-cycle qualification that takes at least four years and requires a *laurea magistrale/specialistica* in either psychology or medicine and surgery, along with professional registration.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] In the Netherlands, the structure of academic studies was altered significantly in 1982 when the "Tweefasenstructuur" (Two Phase Structure) was introduced by the Dutch Minister of Education, Wim Deetman.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] With this structure an attempt was made to standardise all the different studies and to have them conform to similar timetables.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] An additional effect was that students would be forced to produce results within a preset time-frame or otherwise discontinue their studies.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The two-phase structure has been adapted to a bachelor-master structure as a result of the Bologna process.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] In order for a Dutch student to get access to a university education, the student must complete a six-year pre-university secondary education called *voorbereidend wetenschappelijk onderwijs* (VWO).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] There are other routes possible, but only if the educational level of the applicant is comparable to that at the end of the standard two levels is access to university education granted.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] For some studies, specific end levels or disciplines are required, e.g., graduating without having studied physics, biology and chemistry will make it impossible to study medicine.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] People 21 years old, or older, who do not have the required entrance diplomas, may opt for an entrance exam to be admitted to a higher-educational curriculum.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] In this exam, they have to prove their command of disciplines considered necessary for pursuing such study.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] After 1 September 2002, they would be thus admitted to a Bachelor's curriculum, not to a Master's curriculum.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] For some disciplines in the Netherlands, a governmentally determined limited access is in place (although under political review for abolishment, as of February 2011).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] This limits the number of applicants to a specific course of study, thus trying to control the number of future graduates.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The disciplines most renowned for their numerus clausus are medicine and dentistry.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Every year a combination of the highest pre-university graduation grades and some additional conditions determine who can start such a numerus clausus course of study and who can not.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Almost all Dutch universities are government supported, with only a few privately owned universities in existence (i.e. one in business and all others in theology).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Leiden University is the oldest, founded in 1575.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] For medical students the "doctorandus" degree is not equivalent to the European Anglo Saxon postgraduate research degree in medicine, of MD (Medical Doctor).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Besides the title doctorandus, the graduates of the Curius curriculum may also bear the title *arts* (physician).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The doctorandus in medicine title is granted after four years (nominal time) of the Curius curriculum, while the title physician is granted after six years (nominal time) of that curriculum.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The Dutch physician title is equal to a MSc degree according to the Bologna process and can be compared with the MBBS in the UK degree system and the North American MD, but not the UK MD degree, which is a research degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] One-on-one equivalence or interchangeability of the Dutch medical title and MD is often suggested.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] However, officially the MD title is not known, nor legal to use, in the Netherlands.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The correct notation for a Dutch physician who completed his or her medical studies, but did not pursue a doctoral (PhD-like) study is "drs." (e.g.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Jansen, arts*) and not "dr." in medicine, which is often used incorrectly.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] However, like in the United Kingdom, physicians holding these degrees are referred to as 'Doctor' by courtesy.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] In the Netherlands, there is the informal title *dokter* for physicians, but not *doctor* (dr.), unless they also earn such adegree by completing a PhD curriculum.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Furthermore, the *doctorandus* degree does not give a medical student the right to treat patients; for this a minimum of two years of additional study (internship) is required.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] After obtaining a Medical Board registration, Dutch physicians must work an additional two to six years in a field of expertise to become a registered medical specialist.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Dutch surgeons commonly are only granted access to surgical training and positions after obtaining a doctorate (PhD) successfully.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] In recent years, the six-year (nominal time) old Curius curriculum (which offered the titles doctorandus and physician) has been replaced with a three-year (nominal time) Bachelor Curius+ followed by a three-year (nominal time) Master Curius+.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Those who had already begun their old-style Curius curriculum before that will still have to complete it as a six-year study (nominal time).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] A doctorandus in law uses the title *meester* (master, abbreviated as *mr.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Jansen*) instead of drs., and some courses of study, such as in technology and agriculture< grant the title *ingenieur* (engineer, noted as *ir.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] These titles as equivalent to an LL.M (the title "mr.") and to a MSc (the title "ir.") and if gotten before 1 September 2002, from a recognized Dutch university, may be rendered as M (from Master) behind one's name, instead of using the typical Dutch honorifics before one's name.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] However, this M is hardly used in favor of the typical Dutch titles ("drs.", "ir.", "mr."), or MSc, MA or LLM.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Since 1 September 2002, Dutch universities offer specific BSc, BA or LLB studies followed by MSc, MA or LLM studies, thus integrating into the international scientific community, offering lectures, other classes, seminars or complete curricula in English instead of Dutch.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] According to their field of study, MSc graduates may use either ir. or drs. before their names; MA graduates may use drs. before their name; LLM graduates may use mr. before their names, but only if they received such degrees from recognized Dutch universities.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Not uncommonly, the Dutch "drs." abbreviation can cause much confusion in other countries, since it is perceived as a person who has a PhD in multiple disciplines.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] In the Netherlands, the degree MPhil was not awarded after 2009 as the Universiteiten van Nederland refused to recognize the MPhils awarded by Leiden University.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] After successfully obtaining a "drs.", "ir." or "mr." degree, a student has the opportunity to follow a further, promotional course of study (informally called PhD) to eventually obtain a doctorate and subsequently the title "doctor".
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Promotion studies are ideally structured according to a preset time schedule of 4 to 6 years, during which the student has to be mentored by at least one professor.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The promotion study has to be concluded with at least a scientific thesis, which has to be defended to "a gathering of his/her peers", in practice the board of the faculty with guest professors from other faculties or universities added.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] More and more common—and, in some disciplines, even mandatory—is that the student write, and have accepted for publication by peer-reviewed journals, original scientific work.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The number of publications required is often debated and varies considerably between the various disciplines.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] However, in all disciplines the student is obligated to produce and publish a dissertation or thesis in book form.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] All current Dutch academic programs are offered under the Anglo-Saxon bachelor/master structure.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] It takes three years to earn a bachelor's degree and another one or two years to earn a master's degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] There are three official academic bachelor titles (BA, BSc and LLB) and three official master titles (MA, MSc and LLM).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] These academic titles are protected by the Dutch government.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] After obtaining a doctorate, Dutch doctors may bear either the title dr.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] (lower case) before, or the letter D following, their name, but not both simultaneously.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] There is no notation signifying the specific discipline in which the doctorate is obtained.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] As of 1 January 2021, the title 'PhD' and post-nominal degree 'PhD' can also be used, and these are also legally protected.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Stacking of titles, as seen in countries such as Germany (Prof.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Gruber), is highly uncommon in the Netherlands and not well received culturally.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Those who have multiple doctoral titles may use dr.mult. before their name, but this is seldom seen in practice.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The *honoris causa* doctors may use dr.h.c. before their name.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Combining different Dutch titles, especially in different disciplines, is allowed, however, (e.g. mr. dr.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The use of the combination ir. ing. is frequent, indicating one holds a HBO, vocational, or professional engineering degree "ing.", together with an academic engineering degree "ir.".
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] What is not allowed is, after obtaining a doctorate, using dr. drs.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] A combination of a Dutch title with an international title is not allowed, except for some limited number of international professional titles.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Thus, one should choose either one's classical Dutch title or use the shortcut provided by the law following one's name (since 1 September 2002 it is the other way around: those who hold Dutch degrees as MSc, LLM or MA may optionally use the old-style shortcuts before their names).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] "*Doctors*" (dr.) can proceed to teach at universities as "universitair docent" (UD – assistant professor).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] With time, experience and achievement, this can evolve to a position as "universitair hoofddocent" (UHD – associate professor).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Officially an UHD still works under the supervision of a "hoogleraar" (professor), the head of the department.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] However, this is not a given; it is also possible that a department is headed by a "plain" doctor, based on knowledge, achievement and expertise.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The position of "hoogleraar" is the highest possible scientific position at a university and equivalent to the US "full" professor.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The Dutch professor's title, noted as *prof.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Jansen* or *professor Jansen*, is connected to one's employment.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] This means that, should the professor leave the university, he or she also loses the privilege to use the title of professor.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Retired professors are an exception and may continue to note the title in front of their name, or use the title emeritus professor (em. prof.).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] People who switch to a non-university job lose their professorial title and are only allowed to use the "dr." abbreviation.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Unlike some other European countries, such as Germany, Dutch academic titles are used rarely outside academia, hold no value in everyday life, and typically are not listed on official documentation (e.g. passport, drivers license, (governmental) communication).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Dutch academic titles, however, are legally protected and can only be used by graduates from Dutch institutions of higher education.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Illegal use is considered a misdemeanor and is subject to legal prosecution.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Holders of foreign degrees, therefore, need special permission before being able to use a recognised Dutch title, but they are free to use their own foreign title (untranslated).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] In practice, the Public Department does not prosecute the illegal use of a protected title (the Netherlands applies prosecutorial discretion, so some known criminal uses are not prosecuted).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Prior to 1980, there were around 50 different degrees and corresponding educational programs within the Norwegian higher education system.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Degrees had titles that included the gender based Latin term *candidatus/candidata*.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The second part of the title usually consisted of a Latin word corresponding to the profession or training.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] (Candidatus Magisterii) required 4 to 5 years, Cand.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] (Candidatus Realium) required 6 years of study and a scientific thesis in a select set of scientific disciplines (realia).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Over the years these were replaced gradually with degrees that were more and more internationally comparable programs and corresponding titles.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] These degrees were all retired in 2003 in favour of an international system.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The reform of higher education in Norway, *Kvalitetsreformen* ("The Quality Reform"), was passed in the Norwegian Parliament, the Storting, in 2001 and carried out during the 2003/2004 academic year.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] It introduced standard periods of study and the titles *master* and *bachelor (baccalaureus)*.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The system differentiates between a free master's degree and a master's degree in technology.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The latter corresponds to the former *sivilingeniør* degree (not to be confused with a degree in civil engineering, which is but one of many degrees linked to the title *sivilingeniør*, which is still in use for new graduates who can choose to also use the old title).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] All pre-2001 doctoral degree titles were replaced with the title "Philosophical Doctor degree", written *philosophiæ doctor* (instead of the traditional *doctor philosophiæ*).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The title dr. philos. is a substantially higher degree than the PhD and is reserved for those who qualify for such a degree without participating in an organized doctoral degree program.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] In Poland, the system is similar to the German one.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Since 1992, Russian higher education has introduced a multilevel system, enabling higher education institutions to award and issue Bachelor of Science and Master of Science degrees.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] In Russia, Ukraine and some other former USSR republics educational degrees are awarded after finishing a college education.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] There are several levels of education that one must choose in the 2nd and 3rd year of college, usually in the 3rd year of study.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] A specialist degree is awarded after 5 years of college (4 + 1).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] A Master's (Magister) degree is awarded after 6 years of college (4 + 2).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] But a Specialist degree can appear equivalent to Magister degree by reason of taking an equivalent amount of time.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Usually Specialist or Magister degrees incorporate the bachelor's degrees in them, but only the high-level degree is given on the final diploma.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Specialist and Magister degrees require taking final state exams and producing written work on practical application of studied skills or research thesis (usually 70–100 pages) and is roughly equivalent to a master's degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The first-level academic degree is called *Candidate of Sciences* ("Kandidat Nauk").
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Finally, there is a *Doctor of Sciences* ("Doktor Nauk") degree in Russia and some former USSR academic environments.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] This degree is granted for contributions in a certain field (formally – who established new direction or new field in science).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] It requires discovery of new phenomenon or development of new theory or essential development of new direction, etc.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] There is no equivalent of this "doctor of sciences" degree in the US academic system.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] It is roughly equivalent to Habilitation in Germany, France, Austria and some other European countries.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] In countries with a two-tier system of doctoral degrees, the degree of *Candidate of Sciences* should be considered for recognition at the level of the first doctoral degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] According to *Guidelines for the recognition of Russian qualifications in the other countries*, in countries with a two-tier system of doctoral degrees, the degree of *Doktor Nauk* should be considered for recognition at the level of the second doctoral degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] In countries in which only one doctoral degree exists, the degree of *Doktor Nauk* should be considered for recognition at the level of this degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] LL.D. to *Candidate of Sciences of Legal Science*.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Spain's higher-education legal framework includes official and accredited education, as well as non-official education.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] In Spain, accreditation of official university study programmes is regulated by law and monitored by governmental agencies responsible for verifying their quality and suitability for official approval and accreditation.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Official professional study programmes lead to degree qualifications (*Títulos*) with full academic and professional rights.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Master's Degree (*Master Universitario*) – 60 to 120 ECTS Credits in 1–2 years.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Doctoral degree PhD (*Doctorado*) – in 3–4 years.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Accredited bachelor's degrees and master's degrees qualifications will always be described as *Grado* and *Master Universitario*.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] These qualifications comply with the European Higher Education Area (EHEA) framework.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Officially approved and accredited university study programmes by law must implement this framework in order to attain and retain accreditation in Spain.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Not all EHEA-compliant study programmes in Spain are officially approved or accredited by government agencies.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Some universities offer proprietary study programmes as alternatives for a variety of reasons: serving the continuing education market for individual self-advancement and also providing higher education to individuals who have failed to acquire bachelor's degree qualifications.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The main reason for offering these alternative studies, though, is the complex bureaucratic process required to receive the approval of specific titles, in particular when it refers to new studies or studies about matters that do not fit with the official studies.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] For historical reasons, the academic system has been very much under the control of the state, and private universities are still regarded with as a threat to the state system.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] These programmes fall within the category of "non officially approved and accredited" or *estudios no oficiales*, and they confer no academic or professional rights.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] This means that they do not entitle the bearer to claim to have any specific academic or professional qualifications, as far as the Spanish authorities are concerned.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] However, there may be private agreements to recognize the titles.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Universities offering non-official study programmes are legally bound to clearly differentiate between officially-approved and non-officially-approved qualifications.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Non-accredited master's degrees will be described as just *Master*, without the accompanying *Universitario*.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Certain non-officially approved and accredited study programmes may acquire a positive reputation.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] However, neither professional associations, government agencies, judiciary authorities, nor universities – other than the study programme provider – are obliged to recognize non-official qualifications in any way.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] All study programmes must be accredited by ANECA prior to their inclusion in the RUCT.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The RUCT records all officially approved universities and their bachelor's degrees, master's degrees and PhDs and each and every one of the officially approved and accredited study programmes.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Universities are assigned a specific number Code (*Código*) by the RUCT.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The same study programme may acquire different codes as it progresses through various stages of official approval by local and central governments.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Prospective students should check the RUCT Code awarded to the study programme of their interest at every stage of their enquiries concerning degrees in Spain.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] ANECA makes recommendations regarding procedures, staffing levels, quality of teaching, resources available to students and continuity or loss of accreditation.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The ANECA Registry records all events in the life of an officially approved and accredited study programme or a university.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The ANECA Registry Search Facility may be the simplest and safest way to verify the status of all officially approved and accredited study programmes in Spain.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] It is also possible to track qualifications by using the search facility that several Autonomous Communities' own accreditation agencies offer.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The qualifications framework for higher education MECES is the reference framework adopted in Spain in order to structure degree levels.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Not all universities offer degrees named exactly the same, even if they have similar academic and professional effects.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Each university may present proposals for the study programme considered to meet professional and academic demand.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] The proposal will consist of a report linking the study programme being considered and the proposed qualification to be awarded.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] This report will be assessed by ANECA and sent for the Consejo de Universidades Españolas.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] If the *Consejo* agrees with ANECA's approval, it will be included in the RUCT and ANECA registries.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] All bachelor's and master's degrees accredited by ANECA bestow full academic and professional rights in accordance with new and previous laws.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Professional-practice law in Spain is currently under revision.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Before the Bologna Process, the academic degree of a Licentiate was reached after 4 or 5 years of study.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Depending on the official language of the university, it was called *Lizentiat* (German), *Licence* (French) or *licenza* (Italian) and, according to the Bologna reform, is today considered equivalent to a master's degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] A Licentiate with a predefined qualification gave access to the last stage of a further two or more years of studies (depending on the field) for a doctoral degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Apart from this, most universities offered a postgraduate diploma requiring up to two years of study.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] French-speaking universities called them *diplôme d'études approfondies* DEA or DESS, the Italian-speaking university *post laurea* and German-speaking universities mostly *Nachdiplomstudium* (NDS).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Today the federal legislation defines these postgraduate diplomas (60 ECTS credits) as Master of Advanced Studies (MAS) or Executive Master of Business Administration (EMBA) degrees.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Universities may also offer the possibility to gain a diploma in advanced studies (DAS, less than 60 ECTS credits).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] These degrees do not normally give access to a doctoral programme.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Turkish education system has been mostly compatible with the Bologna process before and immediately after adoption.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] New graduates of a bachelor's program from Turkish law faculties are required to enter a legal licensing examination from 2022 onwards, in order to use all the rights to the extent that has been granted by the related laws.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p03] Such requirement does not exist for other degree holders.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] An academic degree is protected under UK law.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] All valid UK degrees are awarded by universities or other degree-awarding bodies whose powers to do so are recognised by the UK government; hence they are known as "recognised bodies".
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The standard first degree in England, Northern Ireland and Wales is the bachelor's degree conferred with honours.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Usually this is a Bachelor of Arts (BA) or a Bachelor of Science (BSc) degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Other variants exist: for example, Bachelor of Education or Bachelor of Laws.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] It usually takes three years to read for a bachelor's degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Candidates who have not achieved the standard for the award of honours may be admitted without honours to the "ordinary" bachelor's degree if they have met the required standard for this lesser qualification (also referred to as a "pass degree").
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Standard levels for each of these classes are 70%+ for a first, 60–69% for a 2:1, 50–59% for a 2:2, 40–49% for a 3rd and 30%+ for a pass degree, although this can vary by institution (e.g. the Open University).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The foundation degree is a qualification, lower than bachelor's level, awarded following a two-year programme of study that is usually vocational in nature.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The foundation degree can be awarded by a university or college of higher education that has been granted foundation-degree-awarding powers by the UK government.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] This degree is comparable to an associate degree in the United States.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The universities of Oxford and Cambridge award honorary Master of Arts (MA) degrees to graduates of their bachelor's programmes, following a specified period of time.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] This is comparable to the practice of the ancient universities in Scotland awarding an MA for a first degree and arguably reflects the rigorous standards expected of their graduates.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Master's degrees such as Master of Arts or Master of Science are typically awarded to students who have undertaken at least a year of full-time postgraduate study, which may require study and involve an element of research.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Degrees such as Master of Philosophy (MPhil) or Master of Letters/Literature (MLitt) are likely to be awarded for postgraduate study involving original research.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] A student undertaking a master's would normally be expected to already hold a bachelor's degree in a relevant subject, hence the possibility of reaching the master's level in one year.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Some universities award a master's as a first degree following an integrated programme of study (an 'integrated master's degree').
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] These degrees are usually designated by the subject, such as Master of Engineering for engineering, Master of Physics for physics, Master of Mathematics for mathematics and so on; it usually takes four years to read for them.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Graduation to these degrees is always with honours.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Master of Engineering in particular has now become the standard first degree in engineering at the top UK universities, replacing the older Bachelor of Engineering.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The Master of Business Administration (MBA) degree is highly valued by those seeking to advance in business as managers and decision makers.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Doctoral degrees or doctorates, such as the Doctor of Philosophy degree (PhD or DPhil) or Doctor of Education (EdD or DEd), are awarded following a programme of original research that contributes new knowledge within the context of the student's discipline.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Doctoral degrees usually take three years full-time.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Therefore, in the UK it may only take seven years to progress from undergraduate to earning a doctorate – in some cases six, since having a master's is not always a precondition for embarking on a doctoral degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] This contrasts with nine years in the United States, reflecting differences in the educational systems.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Some doctorates, such as the Doctor of Clinical Psychology (DClinPsy) qualification, confirm competence to practice in particular professions.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] UK post-secondary qualifications are defined at different levels, with levels 1–3 denoting further education and levels 4–8 denoting higher education.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Within this structure, a foundation degree is at level 5; a bachelor's degree at level 6; a master's degree at level 7; and a doctoral degree at level 8.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Full information about the expectations for different types of UK degrees is published by the Quality Assurance Agency for Higher Education.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] See also graduate certificate, graduate diploma, postgraduate certificate, postgraduate diploma and British degree abbreviations.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The standard first degree for students studying arts or humanities in Scotland is either a Bachelor of Arts or a Master of Arts (the latter traditionally awarded by the Ancient Universities of Scotland for a first degree in an arts/humanities subject).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The standard undergraduate degree for natural and social science subjects is the Bachelor of Science.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Students can work towards a first degree at either ordinary or honours level.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] A general or ordinary degree (BA/MA or BSc) takes three years to complete; an honours degree (BA/MA Hons or BSc Hons) takes four years.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The ordinary degree need not be in a specific subject, but can involve study across a range of subjects within (and sometimes beyond) the relevant faculty, in which case it may also be called a general degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] If a third year or junior honours subject is included, the ordinary degree in that named discipline is awarded.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The honours degree involves two years of study at a sub-honours level in which a range of subjects within the relevant faculty are studied and then two years of study at honours level which is specialised in a single field (for example classics, history, chemistry, biology, etc.).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Not all universities in Scotland adhere to this; in some, one studies in several subjects within a faculty for three years and can then specialise in two areas and attain a joint honours degree in fourth year.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] This also reflects the broader scope of the final years of Scottish secondary education, where traditionally five Highers are studied, compared to (typically) three English or Welsh A-Levels.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The Higher is a one-year qualification, as opposed to the two years of A-Levels, which accounts for Scottish honours degrees being a year longer than those in England.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Advanced Highers add an optional final year of secondary education, bringing students up to the level of their A-Level counterparts – students with strong A-Levels or Advanced Highers may be offered entry directly into the second year at Scottish universities.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Students who complete all the requirements for an honours degree, but who do not receive sufficient merit to be awarded third-class honours, may be awarded a *Special Degree* (ordinary degree – bachelor's level SCQF Level 9).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] In most respects, the criteria for awarding qualifications at honours level and above are the same as in the rest of the UK (see above under England, Wales and Northern Ireland).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Postgraduate qualifications are not designated Master of Arts, as in the rest of the UK, as this is an undergraduate degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Postgraduate degrees in arts and humanities subjects are usually designated Master of Letters (M.Litt.) or, in natural and social sciences, Master of Science (M.Sc.).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Non-doctoral postgraduate research degrees are usually designated Master of Philosophy (M.Phil.) or Master of Research (M.Res.).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The postgraduate teaching qualification is the Postgraduate Diploma in Education (PGDE).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] In Canada, education is the responsibility of the provinces and territories, rather than the federal government.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] However, all of Canada follows the three-level bachelor's-master's-doctorate system common to the Anglophone world, with a few variations.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] A common framework for degrees was agreed between the provinces and territories in 2007.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Bachelor's degrees take normally three to four years, more commonly three years in Quebec (where they follow on from college courses rather than directly from secondary education).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Outside Quebec, three-year bachelor's degrees are normally ordinary degrees, while four-year bachelor's degrees are honours degrees; an honours degree is normally needed for further study at the master's level.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Master's degrees take one to three years (in Quebec they normally take one and a half to two years).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Doctorates take a minimum of three years.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Alone among Canadian provinces and territories, British Columbia offers two-year associate degrees, allowing credit to be transferred into a four-year bachelor's program.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] In Canada, first professional degrees such as DDS, MD, PharmD and LLB or JD are considered bachelor's level qualifications, despite their often being named as if they were doctorates.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] In the province of Quebec, the majority of students must attend college prior to entering university.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Upon completion of a two-year pre-university program, such as in sciences or humanities, or a three-year technical program, such as nursing or computer science, college graduates obtain a *college diploma*, which is a prerequisite for access to university-level studies.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Although these college programs are typical, they are not offered in every institution in the province.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Moreover, while a few other pre-university programs with various concentrations exist, many other technical/career programs are available, depending on the college of choice.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] For example, Dawson College in Montreal has nearly sixty different programs leading to a college diploma.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Special programs, such as physical rehabilitation therapy, are offered in some colleges as well.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] A similar option is offered for college nursing graduates as they can pursue their studies in university to obtain a Bachelor of Nursing in two years (rather than the usual three or four years, depending on whether the student has completed a college diploma in Quebec).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Education in Mexico follows a three-degree system similar to that of Canada and the US.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The pre-university academic level is the *bachillerato* (also called *preparatoria*), similar to high school.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] They can also get the degree of "ingenieria" or "medico" as an engineer or MD, respectively.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] After receiving the *licenciatura*, students may take extra courses called *diplomados* (similar to a certification but issued by a university).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] These courses last 4–12 months and are a means to further study without continuing to the next degree level, and are usually to demonstrate that students are staying up-to-date in their fields.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Most students stay at this level, but some choose to continue to the *maestría*, equivalent to the master's degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Study at the *maestría* level takes 1–3 years and mandates completion of a thesis.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Post-graduate students in Mexico typically enter a master's program after a few years in the workforce and often continue working while studying.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Traditionally, students who have completed the *maestria* may continue on to the *doctorado* or the doctorate.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Doctoral study typically lasts 3–4 years.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] In recent years this schemes has become flexible such that in some PhD programmes, students are accepted before, or not completing, the course of study for a master's.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] In the United States, since the late 19th century, the threefold degree system of bachelor's, master's, and doctorate has been in place but has evolved into a slightly different pattern from the European equivalent.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Department of Education now classifies degrees in six categories: associate degrees, bachelor's degrees, first professional degrees, master's degrees, intermediate graduate qualifications and research doctorates.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The standard academic progression remains bachelor's—master's—(research) doctorate.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] This timetable is only approximate, however, as students in accelerated programs can sometimes earn a bachelor's degree in three years or, on the other hand, a particular dissertation project might take four or more years to complete.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] In addition, a graduate may wait an indeterminate time between degrees before candidacy in the next level or even an additional degree at a level already completed.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Therefore, there is no time limit on the accumulation of academic degrees.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] By far the most common research doctorate is the Doctor of Philosophy (Ph.D.), comprising 98.1% of research doctorates in 2014.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The Doctor of Education (Ed.D.) made up 1.1% (not including Ed.D.s classified as professional degrees rather than research doctorates) and all other research doctorates were less than 1% in total.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Some schools, mostly junior colleges and community colleges and some four-year schools, offer an associate degree that takes two full years of study.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] These may be in professional or academic fields, and the most common awards are the Associate of Arts (A.A.) and Associate of Science (A.S.) degrees.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Articulation agreements may allow credit earned on an associate degree to be counted toward the completion of a bachelor's degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The "first professional degree" is a graduate-level degree program designed to prepare graduates for professional practice in various fields other than academic scholarship and research.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] First professional degrees require a minimum of two years of college-level education prior to entering the program and a minimum of six years of total college-level education (including that undertaken prior to entry) to complete the program.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Most professional degree programs require a prior bachelor's degree for admission and many require seven or eight years of total study.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] M.D., J.D. or D.O. are named as doctorates but should not be confused with research doctorates such as the Ph.D.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] First professional degrees should also not be confused with professional master's degrees such as the M.Arch. and M.B.A., which are classified as master's degrees, or with intermediate graduate qualifications that also bear the title of doctor, such as D.Min. or D.Psy.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Intermediate graduate qualifications lie between the master's level and doctorate.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] They include awards such as the Certificate of Advanced Study, Graduate Diplomas, Professional Engineer status, and Professional Diplomas, as well as specialist degrees such as Education Specialist, Doctor of Ministry, Doctor of Psychology and the Licentiate in Sacred Theology.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] In 21 US jurisdictions, religious institutions can be authorized to grant religious-exempt (rel. exmpt., rel. expt., etc.) degrees without accreditation or government oversight.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Such degrees are used primarily to attain church-related employment.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Traditionally, more men than women attended and earned degrees at the world's universities.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] A milestone was reached in the United States, according to the 2010 census, as women surpassed men in attaining master's degrees, for the first time.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The U.S. census reports that 10.5 million men have master's degrees or higher, compared with 10.6 million women.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The first year that women surpassed men in earning bachelor's degrees was 1996.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Students, the media, and the general public have shown much concern over the value of getting a higher degree in the US ever since the Great Recession of 2007.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Media coverage of the rising costs of higher education and increased student debt have also affected the public's perceptions of whether higher degrees are still worthwhile.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Statistics citing that college graduates make around $1 million more in their lifetimes than those who did not attend college and live longer, healthier lives work in favor of those who argue the continued value of higher degrees.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Studies like the 2011 Learning Gains study by Arum and Roksa, on the other hand, reported that only 55% of students had any learning gains during their first two years of college, which favors the argument that investing in higher education may not still be worth it.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The Australian Qualifications Framework (AQF) covers 10 levels, of which levels 6–10 correspond to academic degrees.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Also included within the higher education system are: diplomas at level 5 (first year of a degree course); advanced diplomas, at level 6 (associate degree level); and graduate certificates and graduate diplomas, both of which are at level 8 (honours degree level).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] In Australia, most degrees are issued ungraded, with bachelor's degrees with honours being the exception.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Doctorates in Australia may be research doctorates (normally titled PhDs), professional doctorates (normally titled to refer to the field of practice, e.g.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Doctor of Engineering) or higher doctorates (also normally titled to refer to the field of practice).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Extended master's degrees are also allowed to have the word 'doctor' in their title if they are in certain fields, but they are not doctoral degrees.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Like Australia, New Zealand has a 10-level qualifications framework (the New Zealand Qualifications Framework – NZQF) and a referencing exercise has found a one-to-one correspondence between the levels of the two frameworks.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] However, the names given to qualifications at different levels are not the same and New Zealand does not have associate degrees, thus only levels 7–10 correspond to academic degrees.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] These are the bachelor's degree (level 7), bachelor honours degree (level 8), master's degree (level 9) and the doctoral degree (level 10).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] In addition to these, the NZQF has certificates across levels 1–6, diplomas at levels 5 and 6, graduate certificates and graduate diplomas at level 7 (bachelor's), and postgraduate certificates and postgraduate diplomas at level 8 (honours).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Another referencing exercise, comparing the NZQF to the 10-level Irish National Framework for Qualifications, found that degrees were comparable but that further work was needed to improve compatibility at the sub-degree levels (1–6).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Non-degree qualifications at levels 7–9 were not included in the study.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] In New Zealand, master's degrees may be awarded with classified honours (1st, 2:1, 2:2, 3rd) or with distinction or merit.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Undergraduate students in Brazilian universities graduate either with a bachelor's degree, a licentiate degree or a technologist degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Bachelor degrees in Brazil normally take four or five years of full-time study to complete, with the exception of the human medicine course, which requires six years.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Licentiate degrees normally take four-years, and are for students who want to qualify as school teachers.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] *Licenciatura* courses exist mostly in mathematics, humanities and natural sciences.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The technologist degree is available in technology-related fields and can be normally obtained in three years.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] These degrees are for entry into industry.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Admission as an undergraduate student to most top public or private universities in Brazil requires that the applicant pass a competitive entrance examination known as the Vestibular.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Contrary to what happens in the United States, candidates must declare their intended university major when they register for the Vestibular.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Although it is theoretically possible to switch majors afterwards (in a process known within the universities as *transferência interna*), that is actually quite rare in Brazil.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Undergraduate curricula tend to be more rigid than in the United States and there is little room to take classes outside one's major.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Individuals who hold either a bachelor's degree, licentiate or technologist are eligible for admission into graduate courses leading to advanced master's or doctor's degrees.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Criteria for admission into master's and doctor's programs vary in Brazil.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Some universities require that candidates take entrance exams; others make admission decisions based solely on undergraduate transcripts, letters of recommendation and possibly oral interviews.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] In most cases, however, especially for the doctorate, the candidate is required to submit a research plan, and one faculty member must agree to serve as supervisor before the candidate can be admitted into the program.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] There are two types of post-graduate programs: *lato sensu* (specialization and MBAs) and *stricto sensu* (professional master's, master's, and doctorate).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Specializations or MBAs are courses that include taking a minimum number of graduate classes (minimum of 360 hours) but with no need to do research nor defend a thesis, only to present final work showing knowledge acquired.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] It is a professional level where theory and practice are focused broadly.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Professional master's or master's degrees usually take one to two years of full-time study.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The emphasis of the thesis must be in adding some value to knowledge, but not necessarily in being original.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Doctoral degrees normally take four additional years of full-time study to complete.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Requirements for obtaining a doctor's degree include taking additional advanced courses, passing an oral qualifying exam, and submitting a longer doctoral dissertation which must represent a significant original contribution to knowledge in the field to which the dissertation topic is related.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] That contrasts with master's thesis, which, in addition to being usually shorter than doctoral dissertations, are not required to include creation of new knowledge or revision/reinterpretation of older views/theories.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The doctoral dissertation is examined in a final oral exam before a panel of at least two members (in the state of São Paulo the preferred number is five, while the other regions prefer three members), usually including one or two external examiners from another university or research institute.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] In Colombia, the system of academic degrees is based in the British model, similar to the U.S. model.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] After completing their "bachillerato" (high school), students can take one of three options.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The first one is called a *profesional* (professional career), which is similar to a bachelor's degree requiring from four to 6 years of study according to the chosen program.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The other option is called a *técnico* (technician); this degree consists of two and a half years of study and prepares the student for technical or mechanical labors.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Finally, the third option is called a *tecnólogo* (equivalent to associate degree) and consists of three years of study.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] After this, students, now called *profesional* (professionals), *técnicos* (technicians) or *tecnólogos* (associates), can opt for higher degrees.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Formal education after the bachelor's degree leads to the master's degree with the title of *maestro* and doctorate degrees, known as *doctorado* (doctorate).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The master's degree normally takes two years.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Students also can take a specialization course, *especialización*, equivalent to a graduate certificate degree, after their bachelor's degree.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] These programs, like in the U.S., are very popular, because it requires only one to two years of study.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] In Colombia, similar to the U.S. system, the students may not go directly to the *doctorado* without having the "master" degree first.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] After completing *enseñanza media* (high school), students receive a *Licenciatura de Enseñanza Media* (high school diploma), which is a requirement for higher education.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Higher-education programs that provide a professional title but not an academic degree are referred to as *carreras técnicas*, which are similar in duration and scope to associate degree programs.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] These are often granted by educational institutions of the type *instituto profesional* (IP) or *centro de formación técnica* (CFT).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Academic degrees in Venezuela start with the *Certificado de Educación Básica* (Certificate of Basic Education), awarded upon completing the 9th grade.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The next degree is earned upon completing the 11th grade and confers the title of *Bachiller en Ciencias* (High School Graduate of Science), *Bachiller en Humanidades* (High School Graduate of Humanities) or *Técnico en Ciencias* (Science Technician).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Titles at the higher-education level usually depend on the institution handing them out.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Technical schools award the student with the title of *Técnico Superior Universitario* (university higher technician, to distinguish from science technician).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Universities award the student with the title of *ingeniero* (engineer) or with the title *licenciado* (licentiate) after completing a five-year program.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The ingeniero degree requires more physics than the licenciado degree, but both take five years.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Some higher-education institutions may award *diplomados* (diploma), but the time necessary to obtain one varies.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Medical doctors are awarded the title "Médico Cirujano" after completing a 6-year course of study.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] Postgraduate education in Venezuela follows the conventions of the United States (being named "master's" and "doctorate" after the programs there).
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The nature of academic degrees from ecclesiastical institutions of education is outlined in the apostolic constitution *Sapientia Christiana*.
[src:doctorate/academic-degree-p04] The core of degrees granted by pontifical universities consists of three levels: the first is the baccalaureate; the second is the licentiate; the third is the doctorate.
[src:doctorate/academic-ranks-in-denmark] Academic ranks in Denmark are the positions and titles of professors, researchers, and administrative personnel held in academia at Danish institutions, and the relations between them.
[src:doctorate/academic-ranks-in-denmark] The titles (MA, ph.d., dr.) are different from any position that a person may have, but some positions will require certain qualifications corresponding to a title.
[src:doctorate/academic-ranks-in-denmark] The positions are regulated through a consolidated act from the Ministry of Higher Education and Science.
[src:doctorate/academic-ranks-in-denmark] In Denmark the word *professor* is only used for full professors.
[src:doctorate/academic-ranks-in-denmark] An associate professor is in Danish called a *lektor* and an assistant professor is called an *adjunkt*.
[src:doctorate/academic-ranks-in-denmark] The qualification requirements correspond to those of ordinary professorships.
[src:doctorate/academic-ranks-in-denmark] This position gives time for the school to raise funds for the permanent professorship, and it was made as the rules do not as such allow promotions from associate to full professor.
[src:doctorate/academic-ranks-in-denmark] The professor MSO position was abolished in 2019 as part of an attempt to limit temporary positions.
[src:doctorate/academic-ranks-in-denmark] Assistant professorships are temporary, but often the institution will open an associate professorship toward the end of the temporary position or the assistant professorship will be part of a tenure-track path to permanent employment.
[src:doctorate/academic-ranks-in-denmark] The use of the term *tenure* in Denmark has been criticized in the grounds that permanent positions are less secure compared to tenure in other countries, since the flexibility of the Danish job markets still makes it easy to fire people in tenured positions.
[src:doctorate/academic-ranks-in-denmark] The term *docent* was used as an additional step between lektor and full professor before 1972, and around 1990 as mark of associate professors with special qualifications.
[src:doctorate/academic-ranks-in-denmark] The Danish PhD does not come with the title *dr.* or *doktor*, only *ph.d.*; only the (higher) doctorate, after a similar extended thesis to the German docent, brings the right to be addressed as *doktor*.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Tenure was introduced into American universities in the early 1900s in part to prevent the arbitrary dismissal of faculty members who expressed unpopular views.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Before Nazism, Germany had been a leader in academic tenure, but free speech and tenure were severely curtailed under the Third Reich.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Adolf Hitler called universal education "the most corroding and disintegrating poison".
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] He appointed Education Minister Bernhard Rust, to ensure Nazi racial theories were integrated in university curriculums.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] This caused a purge of 1500 professors, and by 1939, nearly half of all faculty posts were occupied by Nazis.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] In the late 1940s, the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign fired several untenured economists, all of whom subsequently had distinguished careers, for teaching the "heresy" Keynesian economics.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Danish universities in advertisements for faculty positions usually state that professor positions are tenured.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] What that means has been a matter of controversy.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Denmark adopted a more hierarchical management approach for universities in the early 2000s.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] This new system was introduced by parliament on a proposal by the Minister of Science, Technology and Development, Helge Sander, based on his vision that Danish universities should compete for funding in order to increase their attention to marketing and industry.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Thybo disputed the causes of his firing, and the postdoc said that he did not feel pressured.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] The handling of the firing was criticized by other researchers.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] A later court decision ruled that the dismissal had not followed the collective agreements and Thybo received economic compensation.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Thybo had insisted that he should be reinstated in his previous position, but this was not supported by the court and the university did not rehire him.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] The original form of academic tenure was removed in the United Kingdom in 1988 through the Education Reform Act.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] In its place, there is the distinction between permanent and temporary contracts for academics.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] A permanent lecturer in UK universities usually holds an open-ended position that covers teaching, research and administrative responsibilities.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] In 2010, 9% of academic staff were professors, 66% were "junior staff" (including doctoral candidates on contracts), and 25% were other academic staff in secondary employment.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Permanent research, teaching and management positions below professorship as an "Akademischer Rat" (a civil service position salaried like high school teachers) have become relatively rare compared to the 1970s and 1980s and are often no longer refilled after a retirement.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] This means that, compared to other countries, academics in Germany obtain tenure at a relatively late age, as on average one becomes an Academic Assistant at the age of 42.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] In 2002 the "Juniorprofessur" position (comparable to an assistant professor in the US, but not always endowed with a tenure track) was introduced as an alternative to "Habilitation".
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Due to a university system that guarantees universities relative academic freedom, the position of professor in Germany is relatively strong and independent.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] As civil servants, professors have a series of attendant rights and benefits, yet this status is subject to discussion.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] In the W pay scale the professorial pay is related to performance rather than merely to age, as it was in C.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Under the tenure systems adopted by many universities and colleges in the United States and Canada, some faculty positions have tenure and some do not.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] This statement holds that, "The common good depends upon the free search for truth and its free exposition" and stresses that academic freedom is essential in teaching and research in this regard.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] The statement limits the number of years that any employee can remain employed as a non-tenured instructor or professor, compelling the institution to grant tenure to or terminate an individual, with significant advance notice, at the end of a specified time period.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Some institutions require promotion to associate professor as a condition of tenure.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] A university may also offer research positions or professional track and clinical track academic positions which are said to be "non-tenure track".
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Positions with titles such as instructor, lecturer, adjunct professor, research professor etc. do not carry the possibility of tenure, have higher teaching loads, have less influence within the institution, lower compensation with few or no benefits and little protection of academic freedom.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] In the United States, tenure rights for teachers serving in K-12 public schools also have been in existence for more than a hundred years, beginning first in New Jersey in 1909..
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Defenders of tenure, like Ellen Schrecker and Aeon J.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] "Tenure remains scholars' best defense of free inquiry and heterodoxy," writes Skoble, "especially in these times of heightened polarization and internet outrage.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Moreover, there is no way that the employing institution can provide the kind of retraining that would facilitate such a transformation... even the largest and most well-endowed institution lacks the resources to reevaluate and replace its medieval Islamicists and algebraic topologists every year.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Tenure thus lets the academic community avoid excessive turnover while still ensuring the quality of the institution's faculty.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] To Bruce, this is an argument against tenure, but my point is that the more I am persuaded that there is groupthink orthodoxy afoot, the more I want assurances that I would not get fired if I write an essay on free trade or the Second Amendment or a book on anarchism.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] I take it the counterargument is that the more entrenched the orthodoxy becomes, the less likely a heterodox scholar will be tenured, or even hired, in the first place...
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] I can see that this poses a problem but fail to see how abolishing tenure would help.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] As things stand, some heterodox scholars do get hired and tenured..
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Skoble argues categorically and plainly against critics that say "tenure protects incompetent professors": "My argument is that when this happens, it is a malfunction of the system, not an intrinsic feature of its proper use.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] The way it is supposed to work is that incompetent professors do not get tenure in the first place.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Some have argued that modern tenure systems diminish academic freedom, forcing those seeking tenured positions to profess conformance to the level of mediocrity as those awarding the tenured professorships.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Economist Steven Levitt, who recommends the elimination of tenure (for economics professors) in order to incentivize higher performance among professors, also points out that a pay increase may be required to compensate faculty members for the lost job security.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Organizational theorist Russel Ackoff did not believe in it, and went as far as to deposit a signed but undated resignation letter with the Dean of the Wharton School, to be used if and when the Dean thought it could be appropriate to do so.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Some U.S. states have considered legislation to remove tenure at public universities.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] A further criticism of tenure is that it rewards complacency.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Once professors are awarded tenure, they may begin putting reduced effort into their job, knowing that their removal is difficult or expensive to the institution.
[src:doctorate/academic-tenure] Another criticism is that it may cause the institution to tolerate incompetent professors if they are tenured.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] An ***ad eundem* degree** is an academic degree awarded by one university or college to an alumnus of another, in a process commonly known as **incorporation**.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] An *ad eundem* degree is not an earned degree.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] In the later Middle Ages it was common, when a graduate from one university moved into the neighborhood of another, for the new university to admit the graduate as a courtesy, "at the same degree" (in Latin, *ad eundem gradum*).
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] Thus if someone was a Bachelor of Arts in the university that they had attended, they would likewise be a bachelor of arts of their new university.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] Not every college extended this courtesy to all other colleges, however.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] The practice of incorporation diminished in the early 19th century, but it continues at the University of Oxford, the University of Cambridge, and Trinity College Dublin.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] Requests for *ad eundem gradum* degrees also occurred at Adelaide University in the 1880s.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] A number of female students at Oxford and Cambridge were awarded *ad eundem* University of Dublin degrees at Trinity College Dublin, between 1904 and 1907, at a time when their own universities refused to confer degrees upon women and were nicknamed the "steamboat ladies".
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] Today, graduates of the Universities of Oxford and Cambridge are eligible to apply for corresponding degrees of Trinity College Dublin, and vice versa, provided that they wish to register for a degree at Trinity College or are members of the academic staff, and pay the required fee.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] Rhodes University in South Africa uses the term *ad eundem gradum* to give a student status to undertake a research higher degree based on experience, as opposed to an explicit qualification.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] In this case the student does not acquire a qualification, but is exempt from an entry requirement.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] At the University of Oxford, incorporation first appeared in the University Statutes in 1516, although the practice itself is older: in the 15th and early 16th centuries, incorporation was granted to members of universities from all over Europe.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] In 1861, incorporation was restricted to members of Cambridge University and Trinity College, Dublin.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] In 1908, incorporation was further restricted to specific degrees from these universities.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] While not an earned degree, both original degree(s) and incorporated *ad eundem* degree(s) are given in post-nominals listed in the Oxford University Calendar.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] These attempts were rebuffed by the other universities, and eventually abandoned by Durham.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] Still, Durham granted graduates from other universities degrees *ad eundem* until the practice was abolished by the adoption of new university statutes in 1909.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] In the United States, the *ad eundem* Bachelor of Arts and Master of Arts as a regularly awarded academic qualification from graduates of other colleges and universities generally dates from the colonial period, and was awarded at the institutions listed below.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] Five universities in the United States follow a tradition that only alumni may hold certain faculty positions, and in limited cases preserve the tradition of the *ad eundem* Master of Arts to the present day, with the specific circumstances described below.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] Because these degrees do not involve any further study, many faculty members do not list them on their curricula vitae, although some choose to do so.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] At Harvard the degree is described as given *ut in grege nostro numeretur* ("so that (s)he may be numbered in our flock").
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] At Brown, the degrees have been awarded as a part of the annual May commencement ceremony.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] At Amherst, Wesleyan, and Yale, the degrees are conferred upon those who rise to the rank of full professor.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] Yale refers to this degree as the MA *Privatim*.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] During the 150th anniversary of Princeton University, in 1896, 16 full professors were awarded the MA *Privatim*.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] At Amherst, in recent years, the degrees are awarded during first-year student convocation in August, at Yale it is an "elegant, brief ceremony, usual in February or March", and at Wesleyan as part of commencement in May.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] Amherst College grants this degree to college faculty despite the fact that it grants only bachelor's degrees to its matriculated students.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] However, those professors who already earned a bachelor's degree at Amherst or Wesleyan by attending as an undergraduate are not presented with a second degree.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] In 2024, Amherst College President Michael A.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] In April 2023, the President of Yale, Peter Salovey, awarded M.A.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] *Privatim* degrees posthumously to Reverend James W.
[src:doctorate/ad-eundem-degree] Pennington and Reverend Alexander Crummell, the first two black students at Yale, both of whom faced numerous incidents of discrimination and left Yale without earning degrees.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] A **doctorate** (from Latin *doctor*, meaning "teacher") or **doctoral degree** is a postgraduate academic degree awarded by universities and some other educational institutions, derived from the ancient formalism *licentia docendi* ("licence to teach").
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] In most countries, a research degree qualifies the holder to teach at university level in the degree's field or work in a specific profession.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] There are a number of doctoral degrees; the most common is the Doctor of Philosophy (PhD), awarded in many different fields, ranging from the humanities to scientific disciplines.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Many universities also award honorary doctorates to individuals deemed worthy of special recognition, either for scholarly work or other contributions to the university or society.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The term *doctor* derives from Latin, meaning "teacher" or "instructor".
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The doctorate (Latin: *doctoratus*) appeared in medieval Europe as a license to teach Latin (*licentia docendi*) at a university.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Its roots can be traced to the early church in which the term *doctor* referred to the Apostles, Church Fathers, and other Christian authorities who taught and interpreted the Bible.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The right to grant a *licentia docendi* (i.e. the doctorate) was originally reserved to the Catholic Church, which required the applicant to pass a test, take an oath of allegiance, and pay a fee.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The Third Council of the Lateran of 1179 guaranteed access—at that time essentially free of charge—to all able applicants.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] This right remained a bone of contention between the church authorities and the universities, slowly distancing themselves from the Church.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] In 1213 the right was granted by the pope to the University of Paris, where it became a universal license to teach (*licentia ubique docendi*).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] However, while the *licentia* continued to hold a higher prestige than the bachelor's degree (*baccalaureus*), the latter was ultimately reduced to an intermediate step to the master's degree (*magister*) and doctorate, both of which now became the accepted teaching qualifications.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] According to Keith Allan Noble (1994), the first doctoral degree was awarded in medieval Paris around 1150 by the University of Paris.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] George Makdisi theorizes that the *ijazah* issued in early Islamic madrasahs was the origin of the doctorate later issued in medieval European universities.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Alfred Guillaume and Syed Farid al-Attas agree that there is a resemblance between the *ijazah* and the *licentia docendi*.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Stewart notes a difference in the granting authority (individual professor for the *ijazah* and a corporate entity in the case of the university doctorate).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The doctorate of philosophy developed in Germany in the 17th century (likely c.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The term "philosophy" does not refer here to the field or academic discipline of philosophy; it is used in a broader sense under its original Greek meaning of "love of wisdom".
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] In most of Europe, all fields (history, philosophy, social sciences, mathematics, and natural philosophy/natural sciences) were traditionally known as philosophy, and in Germany and elsewhere in Europe the basic faculty of liberal arts was known as the "faculty of philosophy".
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The Doctorate of Philosophy adheres to this historic convention, even though most degrees are not for the study of philosophy itself.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Chris Park explains that it was not until formal education and degree programs were standardized in the early 19th century that the Doctorate of Philosophy was reintroduced in Germany (in what would become the Humboldt University of Berlin) as a research degree, abbreviated as Dr. phil.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] (similar to Ph.D. in Anglo-American countries).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] University doctoral training was a form of apprenticeship to a guild.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The traditional term of study before new teachers were admitted to the guild of "Masters of Arts" was seven years, matching the apprenticeship term for other occupations.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Originally the terms "master" and "doctor" were synonymous, but over time, the doctorate came to be regarded as a higher qualification than the master's degree.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] University degrees, including doctorates, were originally restricted to men.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The use and meaning of the doctorate have changed over time and are subject to regional variations.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] For instance, until the early 20th century, few academic staff or professors in English-speaking universities held doctorates, except for very senior scholars and those in holy orders.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] After that time, the German practice of requiring lecturers to have completed a research doctorate spread.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Universities' shift to research-oriented education (based upon the scientific method, inquiry, and observation) increased the doctorate's importance.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Today, a research doctorate (PhD) or its equivalent (as defined in the US by the NSF) is generally a prerequisite for an academic career.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] However, many recipients do not work in academia.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Professional doctorates developed in the United States from the 19th century onward.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The first professional doctorate offered in the United States was the MD at Kings College (now Columbia University) after the medical school's founding in 1767.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] However, this was a professional doctorate in the modern American sense.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] It was awarded for further study after the qualifying Bachelor of Medicine (MB) rather than a qualifying degree.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The MD became the standard first degree in medicine in the US during the 19th century, but as a three-year undergraduate degree.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] It did not become established as a graduate degree until 1930.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] As the standard qualifying degree in medicine, the MD gave that profession the ability (through the American Medical Association, established in 1847 for this purpose) to set and raise standards for entry into professional practice.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] In the shape of the German-style PhD, the modern research degree was first awarded in the US in 1861, at Yale University.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] This differed from the MD in that the latter was a vocational "professional degree" that trained students to apply or practice knowledge rather than generate it, similar to other students in vocational schools or institutes.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] In the UK, research doctorates initially took higher doctorates in Science and Letters, first introduced at Durham University in 1882.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The PhD spread to the UK from the US via Canada and was instituted at all British universities from 1917.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The first (titled a DPhil) was awarded at the University of Oxford.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Following the MD, the next professional doctorate in the US, the Juris Doctor (JD), was established by the University of Chicago in 1902.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] However, it took a long time to be accepted, not replacing the Bachelor of Laws (LLB) until the 1960s, by which time the LLB was generally taken as a graduate degree.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Notably, the JD and LLB curriculum were identical, with the degree being renamed as a doctorate, and it (like the MD) was not equivalent to the PhD, raising criticism that it was "not a 'true Doctorate'".
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] When professional doctorates were established in the UK in the late 1980s and early 1990s, they did not follow the US model.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Still, they were set up as research degrees at the same level as PhDs but with some taught components and a professional focus for research work.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Now usually called higher doctorates in the United Kingdom, the older-style doctorates take much longer to complete since candidates must show themselves to be leading experts in their subjects.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] These doctorates are less common than the PhD in some countries and are often awarded *honoris causa*.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] A degree beyond a doctorate, the habilitation is used for academic recruitment purposes in several countries within the EU.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Especially in Germany, it can be a requirement for appointment as a *Privatdozent* or professor.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The habilitation requires the candidate to either produce a second, generally longer thesis or a portfolio of research publications.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The habilitation aims to demonstrate independent and thorough research, experience in teaching and lecturing, and, more recently, the ability to generate supportive funding.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Since the Middle Ages, the number and types of doctorates awarded by universities have proliferated throughout the world.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Practice varies from one country to another.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] While a doctorate usually entitles a person to be addressed as "doctor", the use of the title varies widely depending on the type and the associated occupation.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Research doctorates are awarded in recognition of publishable academic research, at least in principle, in a peer-reviewed academic journal.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The best-known research degree in the English-speaking world is the Doctor of Philosophy (abbreviated PhD or, at a small number of British universities, DPhil) awarded in many countries throughout the world.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] In the US, for instance, although the most typical research doctorate is the PhD, accounting for about 98% of the research doctorates awarded, there are more than 15 other types of research doctorates.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The UK Doctor of Medicine (MD or MD (Res)) and Doctor of Dental Surgery (DDS) are research doctorates.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The Doctor of Theology (ThD or DTh), Doctor of Practical Theology (DPT) and the Doctor of Sacred Theology (STD, or DSTh) are research doctorates in theology.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Criteria for research doctorates vary but typically require completion of a substantial body of original research, which may be presented as a single thesis or dissertation, or as a portfolio of shorter project reports (thesis by publication).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Certain doctoral programs employ alternative assessment models, in which the degree is awarded based on coursework, examinations, or peer-reviewed publications rather than a single monographic dissertation.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The submitted dissertation is assessed by a committee of, typically, internal, and external examiners.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] It is then typically defended by the candidate during an oral examination (called *viva (voce)* in the UK and India) by the committee, which then awards the degree unconditionally, awards the degree conditionally (ranging from corrections in grammar to additional research), or denies the degree.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Candidates may also be required to complete graduate-level courses in their field and study research methodology.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Criteria for admission to doctoral programs vary.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Students may be admitted with a bachelor's degree in the US and the UK.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] However, elsewhere, (e.g., in Finland and many other European countries), a master's degree is required.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The time required to complete a research doctorate varies from three years, excluding undergraduate study, to six years or more.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Licentiate degrees vary widely in their meaning, and in a few countries are doctoral-level qualifications.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Sweden awards the licentiate degree as a two-year qualification at the doctoral level and the doctoral degree (PhD) as a four-year qualification.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Sweden originally abolished the Licentiate in 1969 but reintroduced it in response to demands from business.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Finland also has a two-year doctoral level licentiate degree, similar to Sweden's.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Outside of Scandinavia, the licentiate is usually a lower-level qualification.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] In Belgium, the licentiate was the basic university degree prior to the Bologna Process and was equivalent to a bachelor's degree.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] In France and other countries, it is the bachelor's-level qualification in the Bologna process.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] In the Pontifical system, the Licentiate in Sacred Theology (STL) is equivalent to an advanced master's degree, or the post-master's coursework required in preparation for a doctorate (i.e. similar in level to the Swedish/Finnish licentiate degree).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] While other licences (such as the Licence in Canon Law) are at the level of master's degrees.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] A higher tier of research doctorates may be awarded based on a formally submitted portfolio of published research of an exceptionally high standard.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Countries in the region of Scandinavia offer a higher research doctorate like the *Doctor Medicinae* (*Dr.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The habilitation teaching qualification (*facultas docendi* or "faculty to teach") under a university procedure with a thesis and an exam is commonly regarded as belonging to this category in Germany, Austria, France, Liechtenstein, Switzerland, Poland, etc.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The degree developed in Germany in the 19th century "when holding a doctorate seemed no longer sufficient to guarantee a proficient transfer of knowledge to the next generation".
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] In Austria, the habilitation bestows the graduate with the *facultas docendi, venia legendi*.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] In many Central and Eastern Europe countries, the degree gives the *venia legendi*, Latin for "the permission to lecture", or *ius docendi*, "the right to teach", a specific academic subject at universities for a lifetime.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Higher doctorates may also be awarded as honorary degrees – either on an institution's own initiative or following a nomination – in recognition of public prestige, institutional service, philanthropy or professional achievement.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] In a formal listing of qualifications, and often in other contexts, an honorary higher doctorate may be identified in various ways, including "DCL, *honoris causa*", "Hon LLD" or "LittD *h.c.*".
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Some Latin American countries award a postdoctoral degree, or *posdoctorado* involving structured postdoctoral studies and research.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Depending on the country, this may be called a *diploma de posdoctorado* (postdoctoral diploma), *título de Posdoctorado* (postdoctoral degree) or simply *posdoctorado* (postdoctorate).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Depending on the country, professional doctorates may also be research degrees at the same level as PhDs.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The relationship between research and practice is considered important and professional degrees with little or no research content are typically aimed at professional performance.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] The definition for a professional doctorate does not include a requirement for either a dissertation or study beyond master's level, in contrast to the definition for research doctorates ("doctor's degree – research/scholarship").
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] However, individual programs may have different requirements.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] There is also a category of "doctor's degree – other" for doctorates that do not fall into either the "professional practice" or "research/scholarship" categories.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] All of these are considered doctoral degrees.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] In contrast to the US, many countries reserve the term "doctorate" for research degrees.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] If, as in Canada and Australia, professional degrees bear the name "Doctor of ...", etc., it is made clear that these are not doctorates.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Examples of this include Doctor of Medicine (MD), Doctor of Dental Surgery (DDS) and Juris Doctor (JD).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] In the Philippines, the University of the Philippines Open University offers a Doctor of Communication (DComm) professional doctorate.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] All doctorates in the UK and Ireland are third cycle qualifications in the Bologna Process, comparable to US research doctorates.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Although all doctorates are research degrees, professional doctorates normally include taught components, while the name PhD/DPhil is normally used for doctorates purely by thesis.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Professional, practitioner, or practice-based doctorates such as the DClinPsy, DPsych, MD, DHSc, EdD, DBA, EngD and DAg are full academic doctorates.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] They are at the same level as the PhD in the national qualifications frameworks; they are not first professional degrees but are "often post-experience qualifications" in which practice is considered important in the research context.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] In 2009 there were 308 professional doctorate programs in the UK, up from 109 in 1998, with the most popular being the EdD (38 institutions), DBA (33), EngD/DEng (22), MD/DM (21), and DClinPsy/DClinPsych/ClinPsyD (17).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Similarly, in Australia, the term "professional doctorate" is sometimes applied to the *Scientiae Juridicae Doctor* (SJD), which, like the UK professional doctorates, is a research degree.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] When a university wishes to formally recognize an individual's contributions to a particular field or philanthropic efforts, it may choose to grant a doctoral degree *honoris causa* ('for the sake of the honor'), waiving the usual requirements for granting the degree.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p01] Some universities do not award honorary degrees; for example, Cornell University, the University of Virginia, and Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] In Argentina the doctorate (*doctorado*) is the highest academic degree.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The intention is that candidates produce original contributions in their field knowledge within a frame of academic excellence.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] A dissertation or thesis is prepared under the supervision of a tutor or director.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] It is reviewed by a Doctoral Committee composed of examiners external to the program and at least one examiner external to the institution.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The degree is conferred after a successful dissertation defence.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] In 2006, there were approximately 2,151 postgraduate careers in the country, of which 14% were doctoral degrees.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Doctoral programs in Argentina are overseen by the National Commission for University Evaluation and Accreditation, an agency in Argentina's Ministry of Education, Science and Technology.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The Australian Qualifications Framework (AQF) categorizes tertiary qualifications into ten levels that are numbered from one to ten in ascending order of complexity and depth.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Of these qualification levels, six are for higher education qualifications and are numbered from five to ten.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Doctoral degrees occupy the highest of these levels: level ten.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] All doctoral degrees involve research and this is a defining characteristic of them.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] There are three categories of doctoral degrees recognized by the AQF: research doctorates, professional doctorates and higher doctorates.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Research doctorates and professional doctorates are both completed as part of a programme of study and supervised research.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Both have entry requirements of the student having a supervisor that has agreed to supervise their research, along with the student possessing an honours degree with upper second-class honours or better or a master's degree with a substantial research component.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Research doctorates are typically titled Doctor of Philosophy and they are awarded on the basis of an original and significant contribution to knowledge.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Professional doctorates are typically titled Doctor of (field of study) and they are awarded on the basis of an original and significant contribution to professional practice.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Typically, to be eligible to be awarded a higher doctorate a student must have completed a research doctorate at least seven to ten years prior to submitting the research portfolio used to award them a higher doctorate.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Doctoral candidates are normally required to have a master's degree in a related field.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Exceptions are based on their individual academic merit.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] A second and a third foreign language are other common requirements, although the requirements regarding proficiency commonly are not strict.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The admissions process varies by institution.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Some require candidates to take tests while others base admissions on a research proposal application and interview only.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] In both instances however, a faculty member must agree prior to admission to supervise the applicant.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Requirements usually include satisfactory performance in advanced graduate courses, passing an oral qualifying exam and submitting a thesis that must represent an original and relevant contribution to existing knowledge.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The thesis is examined in a final public oral exam administered by at least five faculty members, two of whom must be external.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] After completion, which normally consumes 4 years, the candidate is commonly awarded the degree of *Doutor* (Doctor) followed by the main area of specialization, e.g.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] *Doutor em Direito* (Doctor of Laws), *Doutor em Ciências da Computação* (Doctor of Computer Sciences), *Doutor em Filosofia* (Doctor of Philosophy), *Doutor em Economia* (Doctor of Economics), *Doutor em Engenharia* (Doctor of Engineering) or *Doutor em Medicina* (Doctor of Medicine).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The generic title of *Doutor em Ciências* (Doctor of Sciences) is normally used to refer collectively to doctorates in the natural sciences (i.e.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] All graduate programs in Brazilian public universities are tuition-free (mandated by the Brazilian constitution).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Some graduate students are additionally supported by institutional scholarships granted by federal government agencies like CNPq (*Conselho Nacional de Desenvolvimento Científico e Tecnológico*) and CAPES (*Coordenação de Aperfeiçoamento do Pessoal de Ensino Superior*).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Personal scholarships are provided by the various FAP's (*Fundações de Amparo à Pesquisa*) at the state level, especially FAPESP in the state of São Paulo, FAPERJ in the state of Rio de Janeiro and FAPEMIG in the state of Minas Gerais.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Competition for graduate financial aid is intense and most scholarships support at most 2 years of master's studies and 4 years of doctoral studies.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The normal monthly stipend for doctoral students in Brazil is between US$500 and $1000.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] A degree of *Doutor* usually enables an individual to apply for a junior faculty position equivalent to a US assistant professor.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Progression to full professorship, known as *Professor Titular*, requires that the candidate be successful in a competitive public exam and normally takes additional years.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] In the federal university system, doctors who are admitted as junior faculty members may progress (usually by seniority) to the rank of associate professor, then become eligible to take the competitive exam for vacant full professorships.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] In recent years some initiatives as jointly supervised doctorates (e.g.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] "cotutelles") have become increasingly common in the country, as part of the country's efforts to open its universities to international students.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] *dr.phil.*, *Doctor Philosophiae*, for humanistic and STEM subjects) – the higher doctorate – introduced in 1479.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The second part of the title communicates the field of study – e.g.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] *dr.scient* (in the sciences), *dr.jur* (in law), *dr.theol* (in theology).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] For the ph.d. degree, the candidates (ph.d. students or fellows) – who are required to have a master's degree – enroll at a ph.d. school at a university and participate in a research training program, at the end of which they each submit a thesis and defend it orally at a formal disputation.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] In the disputation, the candidates defend their theses against three official opponents, and may take opponents or questions from those present in the auditorium *(ex auditorio)*.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The official opponents are required to be full professors.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The candidate is required to have a master's degree, but not necessarily a ph.d.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The original vision was purported to be to phase out the higher doctorate in favor of the ph.d.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] (or merge the two), but so far, there are no signs of this happening.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Many Danish academics with permanent positions wrote ph.d. dissertations in the 90s when the system was new, since at that time, a ph.d. degree or equivalent qualifications began to be required for certain academic positions in Denmark.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Until the late 20th century, the higher doctorate was a condition for attaining full professorship; it is no longer required *per se* for any positions, but is considered amply equivalent to the ph.d. when applying for academic positions.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] In Egypt, the highest degree of doctorate is awarded by Al-Azhar University, which grants habilitation (Arabic: العالمية, romanized: *ālimiyya*).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The medical doctorate (abbreviated as M.D.) is equivalent to the Ph.D. degree.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] To earn an M.D. in a science specialty, one must have a master's degree (M.Sc.) (or two diplomas before the introduction of the M.Sc. degree in Egypt) before applying.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The M.D. degree involves courses in the field and defending a dissertation.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] It takes on average three to five years.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Many postgraduate medical and surgical specialties students earn a doctorate.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] After finishing a 6-year medical school and one-year internship (house officer), physicians and surgeons earn the M.B.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] B.Ch. degree, which is equivalent to a US MD degree.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] They can then apply to earn a master's degree or a speciality diploma, then an MD degree in a specialty.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The Egyptian M.D. degree is written using the name of one's specialty.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] (Geriatrics) means a doctorate in Geriatrics, which is equivalent to a Ph.D. in Geriatrics.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The Finnish requirement for the entrance into doctoral studies is a master's degree or equivalent.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] All universities have the right to award doctorates.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The *ammattikorkeakoulu* institutes (institutes of higher vocational education that are not universities but often called "Universities of Applied Sciences" in English) do not award doctoral or other academic degrees.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Entrance to a doctoral program is available only for holders of a master's degree; there is no honors procedure for recruiting those with only a bachelor's degree.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Entrance is not as controlled as in undergraduate studies, where a strict numerus clausus is applied.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Usually, a prospective student discusses their plans with a professor.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] If the professor agrees to accept the student, the student applies for admission.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The professor may recruit students to their group.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Formal acceptance does not imply funding.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The student must obtain funding either by working in a research unit or through private scholarships.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Funding is more available for natural and engineering sciences than in letters.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Sometimes, normal work and research activity are combined.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Prior to introduction of the Bologna process, Finland required at least 42 credit weeks (1,800 hours) of formal coursework.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The requirement was removed in 2005, leaving the decision to individual universities, which may delegate the authority to faculties or individual professors.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] In Engineering and Science, required coursework varies between 40 and 70 ECTS.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The duration of graduate studies varies.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] It is possible to graduate three years after the master's degree, while much longer periods are not uncommon.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The study ends with a dissertation, which must present substantial new scientific/scholarly knowledge.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The dissertation can either be a monograph or it an edited collection of 3 to 7 journal articles.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Students unable or unwilling to write a dissertation may qualify for a licentiate degree by completing the coursework requirement and writing a shorter thesis, usually summarizing one year of research.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] When the dissertation is ready, the faculty names two expert pre-examiners with doctoral degrees from the outside the university.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] During the pre-examination process, the student may receive comments on the work and respond with modifications.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] After the pre-examiners approve, the doctoral candidate applies the faculty for permission to print the thesis.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] When granting this permission, the faculty names the *opponent* for the thesis defence, who must also be an outside expert, with at least a doctorate.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] In all Finnish universities, long tradition requires that the printed dissertation hang on a cord by a public university noticeboard for at least ten days prior to for the dissertation defence.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The doctoral dissertation takes place in public.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The opponent and the candidate conduct a formal debate, usually wearing white tie, under the supervision of the thesis supervisor.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Family, friends, colleagues and the members of the research community customarily attend the defence.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] After a formal entrance, the candidate begins with an approximately 20-minute popular lecture (*lectio praecursoria*), that is meant to introduce laymen to the thesis topic.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The opponent follows with a short talk on the topic, after which the pair critically discuss the dissertation.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The proceedings take two to three hours.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] At the end the opponent presents their final statement and reveals whether he/she will recommend that the faculty accept it.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Any member of the public then has an opportunity to raise questions, although this is rare.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Immediately after the defence, the supervisor, the opponent and the candidate drink coffee with the public.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Usually, the attendees of the defence are given the printed dissertation.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] In the evening, the passed candidate hosts a dinner (Finnish: *karonkka*) in honour of the opponent.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Usually, the candidate invites their family, colleagues and collaborators.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Doctoral graduates are often Doctors of Philosophy (*filosofian tohtori*), but many fields retain their traditional titles: Doctor of Medicine (*lääketieteen tohtori*), Doctor of Science in technology (*tekniikan tohtori*), Doctor of Science in arts (Art and Design), etc.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The doctorate is a formal requirement for a docenture or professor's position, although these in practice require postdoctoral research and further experience.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Exceptions may be granted by the university governing board, but this is uncommon, and usually due to other work and expertise considered equivalent.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] There was also the less prestigious "university doctorate", ***doctorat d'université***, which could be received for the submission of a single thesis.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] In the 1950s, the *Doctorat ès lettres* was renamed to *Doctorat d'État*.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] After 1984, only one type of doctoral degree remained: the "doctorate" (*Doctorat*).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] A special diploma was created called the "Habilitation to Supervise Research" (also translated as "accreditation to supervise research"; *Habilitation à diriger des recherches*), a professional qualification to supervise doctoral work.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Now habilitation is a prerequisite to the title of professor in university (*Professeur des universités*) and to the title of Research Director (*Directeur de recherche*) in national public research agency such as CNRS, INRIA, or INRAE.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Today, the doctorate (*doctorat*) is a research-only degree.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] It is a national degree and its requirements are fixed by the minister of higher education and research.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Only public institutions award the doctorate.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] It can be awarded in any field of study.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The writing of a comprehensive thesis constitutes the bulk of the doctoral work.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] While the length of the thesis varies according to the discipline, it is rarely less than 150 pages, and often substantially more.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Some 15,000 new doctoral matriculations occur every year and ≈10,000 doctorates are awarded.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Doctoral candidates can apply for a three-year fellowship.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The most well known is the *Contrat Doctoral* (4,000 granted every year with a gross salary of 2300 euros per month as of January 2026).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Since 2002, candidates follow in-service training, but there is no written examination for the doctorate.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The candidate has to write a thesis that is read by two external reviewers.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The head of the institution decides whether the candidate can defend the thesis, after considering the external reviews.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The jury members are designated by the head of the institution.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The candidate's supervisor and the external reviewers are generally jury members.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The maximum number of jury members is 8.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The defense generally lasts 45 minutes in scientific fields, followed by 1 – 2+1⁄2 hours of questions from the jury or other doctors present.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The jury then deliberates in private and then declares the candidate admitted or "postponed".
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] New regulations were set in 2016 and do not award distinctions.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The title of doctor (*docteur*) can also be used by medical and pharmaceutical practitioners who hold a doctor's State diploma (*diplôme d'État de docteur*, distinct from the *doctorat d'État* mentioned above).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] A guideline with good practices and legal analysis has been published in 2018 by the Association nationale des docteurs (ANDès) and the Confédération des Jeunes Chercheurs (CJC) with funding from the French Ministry of research.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Doctoral degrees in Germany are research doctorates and are awarded by a process called ***Promotion***.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Most doctorates are awarded with specific Latin designations for the field of research (except for engineering, where the designation is German), instead of a general name for all fields (such as the Ph.D.).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The concept of a US-style professional doctorate as an entry-level professional qualification does not exist.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Professional doctorates obtained in other countries, not requiring a thesis or not being third cycle qualifications under the Bologna process, can only be used postnominally, e.g., "Max Mustermann, MD", and do not allow the use of the title Dr.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] In medicine, "doctoral" dissertations are often written alongside undergraduate study therefore, European Research Council decided in 2010 that such Dr. med. degrees do not meet the international standards of a Ph.D. research degree.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The duration of the doctorate depends on the field: a doctorate in medicine may take less than a full-time year to complete; those in other fields, two to six years.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Over fifty doctoral designations exist, many of them rare or no longer in use.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] As a title, the degree is commonly written in front of the name in abbreviated form, e.g., *Dr. rer. nat.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Max Mustermann*, dropping the designation entirely.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] However, leaving out the designation is only allowed when the doctorate degree is not an honorary doctorate, which must be indicated by *Dr. h.c.* (from Latin honoris causa).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Although the honorific does not become part of the name, holders can demand that the title appear in official documents.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The honorific is commonly used in formal letters.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] For holders of other titles, only the highest title is mentioned.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Schmidt", for a person who would be addressed as "Prof.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] In the German university system it is common to write two doctoral theses, the **inaugural thesis** (*Inauguraldissertation*), completing a course of study, and the habilitation thesis (*Habilitationsschrift*), which opens the road to a professorship.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Upon completion of the habilitation thesis, a *Habilitation* is awarded, which is indicated by appending *habil.* (*habilitata/habilitatus*) to the doctorate, e.g., *Dr. rer. nat. habil.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] It is considered as an additional academic qualification rather than an academic degree formally.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] It qualifies the owner to teach at German universities (*facultas docendi*).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The holder of a *Habilitation* receives the authorization to teach a certain subject (*venia legendi*).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] This has been the traditional prerequisite for attaining *Privatdozent* (PD) and employment as a full university professor.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] With the introduction of *Juniorprofessuren*—around 2005—as an alternative track towards becoming a professor at universities (with tenure), *Habilitation* is no longer the only university career track.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] In India, doctorates are offered by universities.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Entry requirements include a master's degree.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Some universities consider undergraduate degrees in professional areas such as engineering, medicine or law as qualifications for pursuing doctorate level degrees.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Entrance examinations are held for almost all programs.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] In most universities, the duration of coursework and writing the thesis is 3–7 years.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The most common doctoral degree is a Ph.D.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] In Ireland, doctoral qualifications are classified at Level 10 of the National Framework of Qualifications (NFQ).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The major award types at Level 10 are the doctoral degree and the higher doctorate.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The Irish NFQ is aligned with the Framework for Qualifications of the European Higher Education Area, which supports the international recognition of Irish research degrees.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Ireland has a National Framework for Doctoral Education, which is intended to support excellence in all forms of doctoral education.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The revised 2023 framework sets out principles for doctoral education, including an original contribution to knowledge, a high-quality research environment, supervision and examination arrangements, and a final research thesis comprising work of publishable quality.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Professional doctorates in Ireland are also doctoral-level qualifications.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Quality and Qualifications Ireland states that validation of a professional doctorate requires research accreditation at NFQ Level 10 in the relevant discipline area.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Until the introduction of the *dottorato di ricerca* in the mid-1980s, the *laurea* generally constituted the highest academic degree obtainable in Italy.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The first institution in Italy to create a doctoral program was Scuola Normale Superiore di Pisa in 1927 under the historic name *"Diploma di Perfezionamento"*.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The *dottorato di ricerca* was introduced by law and presidential decree in 1980, in a reform of academic teaching, training and experimentation in organisation and teaching methods.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Italy uses a three-level degree system following the Bologna Process.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The first-level degree, called a *laurea* (bachelor's degree), requires three years and a short thesis.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The second-level degree, called a *laurea magistrale* (master's degree), is obtained after two additional years, specializing in a branch of the field.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] This degree requires more advanced thesis work, usually involving academic research or an internship.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The final degree is called a *dottorato di ricerca* (Ph.D.) and is obtained after three years of academic research on the subject and a thesis.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Alternatively, after obtaining the *laurea* or the *laurea magistrale*, one can complete a "master's" (first-level master's after the *laurea* or second-level master's after the *laurea magistrale*) of one or two years, usually including an internship.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] An Italian "master's" is not the same as a master's degree; it is intended to be more focused on professional training and practical experience.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Regardless of the field of study, the title for Bachelors Graduate students is *Dottore/Dottoressa* (abbrev.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] *Dott.*/*Dott.ssa*, or as *Dr.*), not to be confused with the title for the Ph.D., which is instead *Dottore/Dottoressa di Ricerca*.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] A *laurea magistrale* grants instead the title of *Dottore/Dottoressa magistrale*.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Graduates in the fields of Education, Art and Music are also called *Dr.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Prof.* (or simply *Professore*) or *Maestro*.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Many professional titles, such as *ingegnere* (engineer) are awarded only upon passing a post-graduation examination (*esame di stato*), and registration in the relevant professional association.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Until the 1990s, most natural science and engineering doctorates in Japan were earned by industrial researchers in Japanese companies.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] These degrees were awarded by the employees' former university, usually after years of research in industrial laboratories.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The only requirement is submission of a dissertation, along with articles published in well-known journals.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] This program is called *ronbun hakushi (hakase)* (論文博士).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] It produced the majority of engineering doctoral degrees from national universities.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] University-based doctoral programs called *katei hakushi (hakase)* (課程博士), are gradually replacing these degrees.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] By 1994, more doctoral engineering degrees were earned for research within university laboratories (53%) than industrial research laboratories (47%).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] Since 1978, Japan Society for the Promotion of Science (JSPS) has provided tutorial and financial support for promising researchers in Asia and Africa.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] The only professional doctorate in Japan is the Juris Doctor, known as *hōmu hakushi* (法務博士) The program generally lasts two or three years.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] This curriculum is professionally oriented, but unlike in the US the program does not provide education sufficient for a law license.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p02] All candidates for a bar license must pass the bar exam (*shihou shiken*), attend the Legal Training and Research Institute and pass the practical exam (*nikai shiken* or *shihou shushusei koushi*).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] After successful completion of the first year of university, the student was awarded the propaedeutic diploma (not a degree).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] In some fields, this diploma was abolished in the 1980s.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] In physics and mathematics, the student could directly obtain a *kandidaats* (candidate) diploma in two years.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The candidate diploma was all but abolished by 1989.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] It used to be attained after completion of the majority of courses of the academic study (usually after completion of course requirements of the third year in the program), after which the student was allowed to begin work on their doctorandus thesis.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The successful completion of this thesis conveyed the *doctoranda/us* title, implying that the student's initial studies were finished.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] In addition to these 'general' degrees, specific titles equivalent to the *doctorandus* degree were awarded for law: *meester* (master) (mr.), and for engineering: *ingenieur* (engineer) (ir.).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Following the Bologna protocol the Dutch adopted the Anglo-Saxon system of academic degrees.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The old candidate's degree was revived to become the bachelor's degree and the *doctorandus* (mr and ir degrees) was replaced by master's degrees.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Students can only enroll in a doctorate system after completing a research university level master's degree; although dispensation can be granted on a case-by-case basis after scrutiny of the individual's portfolio.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Research can also be conducted without official research assistant status, for example through a business-sponsored research laboratory.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The doctor's title is the highest academic title in the Netherlands and Flanders.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] In research doctorates the degree is always Ph.D. or dr. with no distinction between disciplines, and can only be granted by research universities.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Every Ph.D. thesis has to be promoted by a research university staff member holding ius promovendi (the right to promote).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] In the Netherlands all full professors have ius promovendi, as well as other academic staff granted this right on individual basis by the board of their university (almost always senior associate professors).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The promotor has the role of principal advisor and determines whether the thesis quality suffices and can be submitted to the examining committee.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The examining committee is appointed by the academic board of the university based on recommendation of the promotor and consists of experts in the field.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The examining committee reviews the thesis manuscript and has to approve or fail the thesis.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Failures at this stage are rare because promotors generally do not allow work to be submutted they deem inadequate to the examining committee, supervisors and promotor lose prestige among their peers should they allow a substandard thesis to be submitted.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] After examining committee approval, the candidate publishes the thesis (generally with DOI: and ISBN indices) and sends it to the examining committee, colleagues, friends and family with an invitation to the public defence.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Additional copies are kept in the university library and the Royal Library of the Netherlands.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The degree is awarded in a formal, public, defence session, in which the thesis is defended against critical questions of the "opposition" (the examining committee).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Specific formalities differ between universities, for example whether a public presentation is given, either before or during the session, specific phrasing in the procedure, and dress code.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] In most protocols, candidates can be supported by paranymphs, a largely ceremonial role, although they are formally allowed to take over the defence on behalf of the candidate.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Doctoral candidates The actual defence lasts exactly the assigned time slot (45 minutes to 1 hour exactly depending on the university) after which the defence is suspended by the bedel who stops the examination with the Latin phrase "Hora Est" (it is time).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Examinations are thus stopped on the clock, frequently mid sentence.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Failure during this session is possible, but extremely rare.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Dutch doctors may use PhD behind their name or the uncapitalized dr. before their name.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Those who obtained a degree in a foreign country can only use the Dutch title dr. if their grade is approved as equivalent by the *Dienst Uitvoering Onderwijs* though according to the opportunity principle, little effort is spent in identifying such fraud.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Those who have multiple doctor (dr.) titles may use the title dr.mult.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Those who have received honoris causa doctorates may use dr.h.c. before their own name.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] In 2023, a pilot started at universities of applied sciences with a professional doctoral programme, in which the focus is on applying knowledge to improve or solve professional processes or products.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] In Belgium's Flemish Community the doctorandus title was only used by those who actually started their doctoral work.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Doctorandus is still used as a synonym for a Ph.D. student.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The *licentiaat* (licensee) title was in use for a regular graduate until the Bologna reform changed the licentiaat degree to the master's degree (the Bologna reform abolished the two-year kandidaat degree and introduced a three-year academic bachelor's degree instead).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] In Poland, an academic degree of *doktor* 'doctor' is awarded in sciences and arts upon an examination and defence of a doctoral dissertation.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] As Poland is a signatory to the Bologna Process, doctoral studies are a third cycle of studies following the bachelor's (*licencjat*) and master's (*magister*) degrees or their equivalents.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Doctoral student is known as *doktorant* (masculine form) or *doktorantka* (feminine form).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Doctorate is awarded within specified branch and discipline of science or art by university or research institute accredited by the minister responsible for higher education.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The title is abbreviated to *dr* in nominative case.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Doctors may further undergo the habilitation process.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Introduced in 1819 in the Russian Empire, the academic title *Doctor of the Sciences* (Russian: Доктор наук) marks the highest academic level achievable by a formal process.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The title was abolished with the end of the Empire in 1917 and revived by the USSR in 1934 along with a new (lower) complementary degree of a *Candidate [Doctor] of the Sciences'* (Russian: Кандидат наук).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] This system has been used since with minor adjustments.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The *Candidate of the Sciences* title is usually seen as roughly equivalent to research doctorates in Western countries while the *Doctor of the Sciences* title is relatively rare and retains its exclusivity.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Most "Candidates" never reach the "Doctor of the Sciences" title.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Similar title systems were adopted by many of the Soviet bloc countries.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Doctoral degrees are regulated by Royal Decree (R.D.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] They are granted by the university on behalf of the king.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Its diploma has the force of a public document.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The Ministry of Science keeps a national registry of theses called TESEO.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] According to the National Institute of Statistics (INE), fewer than 5% of M.Sc. degree holders are admitted to Ph.D. programmes.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] All doctoral programs are research-oriented.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Since September 2012 and regulated by Royal Decree (R.D.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] 99/2011) (in Spanish), three marks can be granted: Unsatisfactory (*No apto*), Pass (*Apto*) and "Cum laude" (*Apto Cum Laude*) as maximum mark.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] In the public defense the doctor is notified if the thesis has passed or not passed.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The *Apto Cum Laude* mark is awarded after the public defense as the result of a private, anonymous vote.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] A unanimous vote of the reviewers nominates Doctors granted *Apto Cum Laude* for an "Extraordinary Award" (*Premio Extraordinario de Doctorado*).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] An approved project earns a master's degree that grants access to a Ph.D. program and initiates the period of research.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] A doctorate is required in order to teach at a university.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Some universities offer an online Ph.D. model.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Only Ph.D. holders, Grandees and Dukes can sit and cover their heads in the presence of the King.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] From 1857, Complutense University was the only one in Spain authorised to confer the doctorate.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] This law remained in effect until 1954, when the University of Salamanca joined in commemoration of its septcentenary.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] In 1970, the right was extended to all Spanish universities.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] All doctorate holders are reciprocally recognised as equivalent in Germany and Spain (according to the "Bonn Agreement of November 14, 1994").
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The doctorate has long existed in the UK as, originally, the second degree in divinity, law, medicine and music.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] But it was not until the late 19th century that the research doctorate, now known as the higher doctorate, was introduced.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The first higher doctorate was the Doctor of Science at Durham University, introduced in 1882.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The PhD was adopted in the UK following a joint decision in 1917 by British universities, although it took much longer for it to become established.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Oxford became the first university to institute the new degree, although naming it the DPhil.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The PhD was often distinguished from the earlier higher doctorates by distinctive academic dress.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] At Cambridge, for example, PhDs wear a master's gown with scarlet facings rather than the full scarlet gown of the higher doctors, while the University of Wales gave PhDs crimson gowns rather than scarlet.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Professional doctorates were introduced in Britain in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The earliest professional doctorates were in the social sciences, including the Doctor of Business Administration (DBA), Doctor of Education (EdD) and Doctor of Clinical Psychology (DClinPsy).
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] *Professional / practice-based / practitioner doctorates* – e.g.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] In the UK, the doctorate is a qualification awarded at FHEQ level 8/level 12 of the FQHEIS on the national qualifications frameworks.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The higher doctorates are stated to be "A higher level of award", which is not covered by the qualifications frameworks.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] These are the most common doctorates in the UK and are normally awarded as PhDs.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] While the master/apprentice model was traditionally used for British PhDs, since 2003 courses have become more structured, with students taking courses in research skills and receiving training for professional and personal development.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] However, the assessment of the PhD remains based on the production of a thesis or equivalent and its defence at a *viva voce* oral examination, normally held in front of at least two examiners, one internal and one external.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Access to PhDs normally requires an upper second class or first class bachelor's degree, or a master's degree.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Courses normally last three years, although it is common for students to be initially registered for MPhil degrees and then formally transferred onto the PhD after a year or two.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Students who are not considered likely to complete a PhD may be offered the opportunity to complete an MPhil instead.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Integrated doctorates, originally known as 'New Route PhDs', were introduced from 2000 onwards.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] These integrate teaching at master's level during the first one or two years of the degree, either alongside research or as a preliminary to starting research.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] These courses usually offer a master's-level exit degree after the taught courses are completed.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] While passing the taught elements is often required, examination of the final doctorate is still by thesis (or equivalent) alone.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The duration of integrated doctorates is a minimum of four years, with three years spent on the research component.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] In 2013, Research Councils UK issued a 'Statement of Expectations for Postgraduate Training', which lays out the expectations for training in PhDs funded by the research councils.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The statement also encourages peer-group development through cohort training and/or Graduate schools.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Higher doctorates are awarded in recognition of a substantial body of original research undertaken over the course of many years.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Usually an examination fee is required, with the examiners examining the whole body of work submitted rather than a single thesis.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] For Doctors of Music, the traditional form of submission is a large body of musical compositions within a portfolio plus commentary, though some universities may allow for other forms of work to be submitted rather than purely musical compositions.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The higher doctorate is similar in some respects to the habilitation in some European countries.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] However, the purpose of the award is significantly different.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] While the habilitation formally determines whether an academic is suitably qualified to be a university professor, the higher doctorate does not qualify the holder for a position but rather recognises their contribution to research.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] The DSc was offered by all 49 responding institutions in 2008 and 15 out of 16 in 2013 and the DLitt by only one less in each case, while the DD was offered in 10 responding institutions in 2008 and 3 in 2013.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] In terms of number of higher doctorates awarded (not including honorary doctorates) the DSc was most popular, but the number of awards was very low: the responding institutions had averaged an award of at most one earned higher doctorate per year over the period 2003–2013.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] Award of substantive higher doctorates remain relatively rare, due to many people not being aware of them or due to the fact that people think they are only given out as honorary degrees on graduation day.
[src:doctorate/doctorate-p03] This has led to many institutions no longer offering/awarding them as substantive degrees.
